====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[198]:0,38
I was born and raised in Kuwait City.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[198]:38,165
My family was one of the few “lucky” ones not to be expelled after 1991, after Arafat sided with Saddam against the world.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[198]:165,216
We weren’t rich, but neither were we struggling.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[198]:216,299
I was comfortable, even sheltered, you might say, and oh did it show in my actions.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[199]:0,115
I watched the Al Jazeera broadcast from behind the counter at the Starbucks where I worked every day after school.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[199]:115,172
It was the afternoon rush hour and the place was packed.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[199]:172,230
You should have heard the uproar, the jeers and catcalls.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[199]:230,307
I’m sure our noise level matched that on the floor of the General Assembly.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[200]:0,57
Of course we thought it was a Zionist lie, who didn’t?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[200]:57,222
When the Israeli ambassador announced to the UN General Assembly that his country was enacting a policy of “voluntary quarantine,” what was I supposed to think?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[200]:222,378
Was I supposed to really believe his crazy story that African rabies was actually some new plague that transformed dead bodies into bloodthirsty cannibals?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[200]:378,485
How can you possibly believe that kind of foolishness, especially when it comes from your most hated enemy?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[201]:0,324
I didn’t even hear the second part of that fat bastard’s speech, the part about offering asylum, no questions asked, to any foreign-born Jew, any foreigner of Israeli-born parents, any Palestinian living in the formerly occupied territories, and any Palestinian whose family had once lived within the borders of Israel.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[201]:324,411
The last part applied to my family, refugees from the ’67 War of Zionist aggression.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[201]:411,576
At the heeding of the PLO leadership, we had fled our village believing we could return as soon as our Egyptian and Syrian brothers had swept the Jews into the sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[201]:576,677
I had never been to Israel, or what was about to be absorbed into the new state of Unified Palestine.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[202]
What did you think was behind the Israeli ruse?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[203]:0,240
Here’s what I thought: The Zionists have just been driven out of the occupied territories, they say they left voluntarily, just like Lebanon, and most recently the Gaza Strip, but really, just like before, we knew we’d driven them out.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[203]:240,577
They know that the next and final blow would destroy that illegal atrocity they call a country, and to prepare for that final blow, they’re attempting to recruit both foreign Jews as cannon fodder and…and—I thought I was so clever for figuring this part out—kidnapping as many Palestinians as they could to act as human shields!
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[203]:577,600
I had all the answers.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[203]:600,627
Who doesn’t at seventeen?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[204]:0,74
My father wasn’t quite convinced of my ingenious geopolitical insights.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[204]:74,110
He was a janitor at Amiri Hospital.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[204]:110,188
He’d been on duty the night it had its first major African rabies outbreak.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[204]:188,404
He hadn’t personally seen the bodies rise from their slabs or the carnage of panicked patients and security guards, but he’d witnessed enough of the aftermath to convince him that staying in Kuwait was suicidal.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[204]:404,480
He’d made up his mind to leave the same day Israel made their declaration.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[205]
That must have been difficult to hear.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:0,18
It was blasphemy!
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:18,92
I tried to make him see reason, to convince him with my adolescent logic.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:92,232
I’d show the images from Al Jazeera, the images coming out of the new West Bank state of Palestine; the celebrations, the demonstrations.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:232,289
Anyone with eyes could see total liberation was at hand.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:289,423
The Israelis had withdrawn from all the occupied territory and were actually preparing to evacuate Al Quds, what they call Jerusalem!
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:423,590
All the factional fighting, the violence between our various resistance organizations, I knew that would die down once we unified for the final blow against the Jews.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:590,621
Couldn’t my father see this?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[206]:621,762
Couldn’t he understand that, in a few years, a few months, we would be returning to our homeland, this time as liberators, not as refugees.
