It was “resolved” after the second outbreak, the larger one at Al Jahrah.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[208]:121,249
My father had just quit his job, cleared out our bank account, such as it was…our bags were packed…our e-tickets confirmed.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[208]:249,339
The TV was blaring in the background, riot police storming the front entrance of a house.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[208]:339,393
You couldn’t see what they were shooting at inside.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[208]:393,507
The official report blamed the violence on “pro-Western extremists.” My father and I were arguing, as always.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[208]:507,657
He tried to convince me of what he’d seen at the hospital, that by the time our leaders acknowledged the danger, it would be too late for any of us.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[209]:0,270
I, of course, scoffed at his timid ignorance, at his willingness to abandon “The Struggle.” What else could I expect from a man who’d spent his whole life scrubbing toilets in a country that treated our people only slightly better than its Filipino guest workers.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[209]:270,317
He’d lost his perspective, his self-respect.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[209]:317,429
The Zionists were offering the hollow promise of a better life, and he was jumping at it like a dog with scraps.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[210]
My father tried, with all the patience he could muster, to make me see that he had no more love for Israel than the most militant Al Aqsa martyr, but they seemed to be the only country actively preparing for the coming storm, certainly the only one that would so freely shelter and protect our family.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[211]:0,23
I laughed in his face.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[211]:23,213
Then I dropped the bomb: I told him that I’d already found a website for the Children of Yassin 1 and was waiting for an e-mail from a recruiter supposedly operating right in Kuwait City.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[211]:213,365
I told my father to go and be the yehud’s whore if he wanted, but the next time we’d meet was when I would be rescuing him from an internment camp.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[211]:365,435
I was quite proud of those words, I thought they sounded very heroic.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[211]:435,592
I glared in his face, stood from the table, and made my final pronouncement: “Surely the vilest of beasts in Allah’s sight are those who disbelieve!” 2
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[212]:0,46
The dinner table suddenly became very silent.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[212]:46,102
My mother looked down, my sisters looked at each other.
