Our proposal to the White House.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[273]:33,195
We outlined a fully comprehensive program, not only to eliminate the threat within the United States, but to roll back and contain it throughout the entire world.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[274]
What happened?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[275]:0,33
The White House loved Phase One.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[275]:33,99
It was cheap, fast, and if executed properly, 100 percent covert.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[275]:99,177
Phase One involved the insertion of Special Forces units into infested areas.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[275]:177,234
Their orders were to investigate, isolate, and eliminate.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[276]
Eliminate?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[277]
With extreme prejudice.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[278]
Those were the Alpha teams?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[279]:0,46
Yes, sir, and they were extremely successful.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[279]:46,219
Even though their battle record is sealed for the next 140 years, I can say that it remains one of the most outstanding moments in the history of America’s elite warriors.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[280]
So what went wrong?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[281]:0,89
Nothing, with Phase One, but the Alpha teams were only supposed to be a stopgap measure.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[281]:89,191
Their mission was never to extinguish the threat, only delay it long enough to buy time for Phase Two.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[282]
But Phase Two was never completed.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[283]
Never even begun, and herein lies the reason why the American military was caught so shamefully unprepared.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[284]:0,137
Phase Two required a massive national undertaking, the likes of which hadn’t been seen since the darkest days of the Second World War.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[284]:137,280
That kind of effort requires Herculean amounts of both national treasure and national support, both of which, by that point, were nonexistent.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[284]:280,355
The American people had just been through a very long and bloody conflict.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[284]:355,372
They were tired.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[284]:372,393
They’d had enough.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[284]:393,482
Like the 1970s, the pendulum was swinging from a militant stance to a very resentful one.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:0,101
In totalitarian regimes—communism, fascism, religious fundamentalism—popular support is a given.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:101,265
You can start wars, you can prolong them, you can put anyone in uniform for any length of time without ever having to worry about the slightest political backlash.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:265,309
In a democracy, the polar opposite is true.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:309,373
Public support must be husbanded as a finite national resource.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:373,458
It must be spent wisely, sparingly, and with the greatest return on your investment.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:458,572
America is especially sensitive to war weariness, and nothing brings on a backlash like the perception of defeat.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:572,645
I say “perception” because America is a very all-or-nothing society.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:645,714
We like the big win, the touchdown, the knockout in the first round.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:714,837
We like to know, and for everyone else to know, that our victory wasn’t only uncontested, it was positively devastating.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:837,893
If not…well…look at where we were before the Panic.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:893,952
We didn’t lose the last brushfire conflict, far from it.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:952,1070
We actually accomplished a very difficult task with very few resources and under extremely unfavorable circumstances.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:1070,1198
We won, but the public didn’t see it that way because it wasn’t the blitzkrieg smackdown that our national spirit demanded.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:1198,1309
Too much time had gone by, too much money had been spent, too many lives had been lost or irrevocably damaged.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[285]:1309,1386
We’d not only squandered all our public support, we were deeply in the red.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[286]:0,48
Think about just the dollar value of Phase Two.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[286]:48,123
Do you know the price tag of putting just one American citizen in uniform?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[286]:123,279
And I don’t just mean the time that he’s actively in that uniform: the training, the equipment, the food, the housing, the transport, the medical care.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[286]:279,435
I’m talking about the long-term dollar value that the country, the American taxpayer, has to shell out to that person for the rest of their natural life.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[286]:435,543
This is a crushing financial burden, and in those days we barely had enough funding to maintain what we had.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:0,185
Even if the coffers hadn’t been empty, if we’d had all the money to make all the uniforms we needed to implement Phase Two, who do you think we could have conned into filling them?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:185,238
This goes to the heart of America’s war weariness.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:238,490
As if the “traditional” horrors weren’t bad enough—the dead, the disfigured, the psychologically destroyed—now you had a whole new breed of difficulties, “The Betrayed.” We were a volunteer army, and look what happened to our volunteers.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:490,689
How many stories do you remember about some soldier who had his term of service extended, or some exreservist who, after ten years of civilian life, suddenly found himself recalled into active duty?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:689,742
How many weekend warriors lost their jobs or houses?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:742,816
How many came back to ruined lives, or, worse, didn’t come back at all?
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:816,871
Americans are an honest people, we expect a fair deal.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:871,1002
I know that a lot of other cultures used to think that was naïve and even childish, but it’s one of our most sacred principles.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[287]:1002,1103
To see Uncle Sam going back on his word, revoking people’s private lives, revoking their freedom…
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[288]:0,155
After Vietnam, when I was a young platoon leader in West Germany, we’d had to institute an incentives program just to keep our soldiers from going AWOL.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[288]:155,332
After this last war, no amount of incentives could fill our depleted ranks, no payment bonuses or term reductions, or online recruiting tools disguised as civilian video games.
====
/html/body/div/div[1]/p[288]:332,480
1 This generation had had enough, and that’s why when the undead began to devour our country, we were almost too weak and vulnerable to stop them.
