/html/body/div/div[5]/p[53]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:0,47
We didn’t know that there was a Great Panic.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:47,76
We were completely isolated.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:76,229
About a month before it began, about the same time as that American newswoman broke the story, our camp was placed on indefinite communication blackout.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:229,327
All the televisions were removed from the barracks, all the personal radios and cell phones, too.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:327,396
I had one of those cheap disposable types with five prepaid minutes.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:396,432
It was all my parents could afford.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[54]:432,519
I was supposed to use it to call them on my birthday, my first birthday away from home.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[55]:0,80
We were stationed in North Ossetia, Alania, one of our wild southern republics.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[55]:80,190
Our official duty was “peacekeeping,” preventing ethnic strife between the Ossetia and Ingush minorities.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[55]:190,262
Our rotation was up about the same time they cut us off from the world.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[55]:262,310
A matter of “state security” they called it.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[56]
Who were “they”?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[57]:0,125
Everyone: our officers, the Military Police, even a plain-clothed civilian who just seemed to appear one day out of nowhere.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[57]:125,178
He was a mean little bastard, with a thin, rat face.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[57]:178,222
That’s what we called him: “Rat Face.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[58]
Did you ever try to find out who he was?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:0,21
What, me personally?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:21,28
Never.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:28,53
Neither did anyone else.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:53,91
Oh, we griped; soldiers always gripe.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:91,148
But there also wasn’t time for any serious complaints.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:148,231
Right after the blackout was put into effect, we were placed on full combat alert.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:231,338
Up until then it had been easy duty—lazy, monotonous, and broken only by the occasional mountain stroll.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:338,421
Now we were in those mountains for days at a time with full battle dress and ammo.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:421,460
We were in every village, every house.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[59]:460,551
We questioned every peasant and traveler and…I don’t know…goat that crossed our path.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[60]:0,17
Questioned them?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[60]:17,26
For what?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[61]:0,17
I didn’t know.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[61]:17,192
“Is everyone in your family present?” “Has anyone gone missing?” “Has anyone been attacked by a rabid animal or man?” That was the part that confused me the most.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[61]:192,199
Rabid?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[61]:199,238
I understood the animal part, but man?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[61]:238,421
There were a lot of physical inspections, too, stripping these people to their bare skin while the medics searched every inch of their bodies for…something…we weren’t told what.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:0,37
It didn’t make sense, nothing did.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:37,185
We once found a whole cache of weapons, 74s, a few older 47s, plenty of ammo, probably bought from some corrupt opportunist right in our battalion.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:185,377
We didn’t know who the weapons belonged to; drug runners, or the local gangsters, maybe even those supposed “Reprisal Squads” that were the reason for our deployment in the first place.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:377,397
And what did we do?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:397,413
We left it all.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:413,509
That little civilian, “Rat Face,” he had a private meeting with some of the village elders.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[62]:509,640
I don’t know what was discussed, but I can tell you that they looked scared half to death: crossing themselves, praying silently.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:0,24
We didn’t understand.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:24,49
We were confused, angry.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:49,111
We didn’t understand what the hell we were doing out there.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:111,164
We had this one old veteran in our platoon, Baburin.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:164,216
He’d fought in Afghanistan and twice in Chechnya.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:216,311
It was rumored that during Yeltsin’s crackdown, his BMP 1 was the first to fire on the Duma.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:311,353
We used to like to listen to his stories.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[63]:353,439
