====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[72]:525,584
What if they were threatening our loved ones…my parents?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[72]:584,666
All the fear, all the doubt, every tangled, negative emotion all fused into rage.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[72]:666,689
“We want to go home!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[72]:689,805
We want to go home!” Chanting, chanting, and then…A round cracked past my ear and Arkady’s left eye imploded.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[72]:805,859
I don’t remember running, or inhaling the tear gas.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[72]:859,1085
I don’t remember when the Spetznaz commandos appeared, but suddenly they were all around us, beating us down, shackling us together, one of them stepping on my chest so hard I thought I was going to die right then and there.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[73]
Was that the Decimation?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[74]:0,28
No, that was the beginning.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[74]:28,71
We weren’t the first army unit to rebel.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[74]:71,146
It had actually started about the time the MPs first closed down the base.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[74]:146,251
About the time we staged our little “demonstration,” the government had decided how to restore order.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[75]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[76]
[She straightens her uniform, composes herself before speaking.]
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[77]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[78]
To “decimate”…I used to think it meant just to wipe out, cause horrible damage, destroy…it actually means to kill by a percentage of ten, one out of every ten must die…and that’s exactly what they did to us.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:0,79
The Spetznaz had us assemble on the parade ground, full dress uniform no less.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:79,286
Our new commanding officer gave a speech about duty and responsibility, about our sworn oath to protect the motherland, and how we had betrayed that oath with our selfish treachery and individual cowardice.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:286,328
I’d never heard words like that before.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:328,417
“Duty?” “Responsibility?” Russia, my Russia, was nothing but an apolitical mess.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:417,495
We lived in chaos and corruption, we were just trying to get through the day.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:495,702
Even the army was no bastion of patriotism; it was a place to learn a trade, get food and a bed, and maybe even a little money to send home when the government decided it was convenient to pay its soldiers.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:702,784
“Oath to protect the motherland?” Those weren’t the words of my generation.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:784,1066
That was what you’d hear from old Great Patriotic War veterans, the kind of broken, demented geezers who used to besiege Red Square with their tattered Soviet banners and their rows and rows of medals pinned to their faded, moth-eaten uniforms. Duty to the motherland was a joke.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:1066,1091
But I wasn’t laughing.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:1091,1126
I knew the executions were coming.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:1126,1248
The armed men surrounding us, the men in the guard towers, I was ready, every muscle in my body was tensing for the shot.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[79]:1248,1279
And then I heard those words…
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[80]:0,62
“You spoiled children think democracy is a God-given right.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[80]:62,92
You expect it, you demand it!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[80]:92,154
Well, now you’re going to get your chance to practice it.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[81]
His exact words, stamped behind my eyelids for the rest of my life.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[82]
What did he mean?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:0,54
We would be the ones to decide who would be punished.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:54,151
Broken up into groups of ten, we would have to vote on which one of us was going to be executed.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:151,234
And then we…the soldiers, we would be the ones to personally murder our friends.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:234,278
They rolled these little pushcarts past us.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:278,318
I can still hear their creaking wheels.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:318,390
They were full of stones, about the size of your hand, sharp and heavy.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:390,445
Some cried out, pleaded with us, begged like children.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[83]:445,572
Some, like Baburin, simply knelt there silently, on this knees, staring right into my face as I brought the rock down into his.
====
