I didn’t have the heart to tell him that Señor Montana had used a sixteen A-1.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[97]:0,69
There was the political comedy guy, you know, the one with the show.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[97]:69,341
He was snorting blow between the air bags of this teeny Thai stripper while spewing about how what was happening wasn’t just about the living versus the dead, it would send shock waves through every facet of our society: social, economic, political, even environmental.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[97]:341,510
He said that, subconsciously, everyone already knew the truth during the “Great Denial,” and that’s why they wigged out so hard when the story was finally broken.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[97]:510,632
It all actually kinda made sense, until he started spewing about high fructose corn syrup and the feminization of America.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[98]:0,80
Crazy, I know, but you kinda expected those people to be there, at least I did.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[98]:80,288
What I didn’t expect was all their “people.” Every one of them, no matter who they were or what they did, had to have, at least, I don’t know how many stylists and publicists and personal assistants.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[98]:288,406
Some of them, I think, were pretty cool, just doing it for the money, or because they figured they’d be safe there.
