Personally, I think that’s a big ’ole sack of it.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:309,523
Sure, we were unprepared, our tools, our training, everything I just talked about, all one class-A, gold-standard clusterfuck, but the weapon that really failed wasn’t something that rolled off an assembly line.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:523,581
It’s as old as…I don’t know, I guess as old as war.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:581,783
It’s fear, dude, just fear and you don’t have to be Sun freakin Tzu to know that real fighting isn’t about killing or even hurting the other guy, it’s about scaring him enough to call it a day.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:783,972
Break their spirit, that’s what every successful army goes for, from tribal face paint to the “blitzkrieg” to…what did we call the first round of Gulf War Two, “Shock and Awe”?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:972,1007
Perfect name, “Shock and Awe”!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:1007,1058
But what if the enemy can’t be shocked and awed?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:1058,1102
Not just won’t, but biologically can’t!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:1102,1218
That’s what happened that day outside New York City, that’s the failure that almost lost us the whole damn war.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:1218,1348
The fact that we couldn’t shock and awe Zack boomeranged right back in our faces and actually allowed Zack to shock and awe us!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:1348,1370
They’re not afraid!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[202]:1370,1452
No matter what we do, no matter how many we kill, they will never, ever be afraid!
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[203]:0,143
Yonkers was supposed to be the day we restored confidence to the American people, instead we practically told them to kiss their ass good-bye.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[203]:143,248
If it wasn’t for the Sou’frican Plan, I have no doubt, we’d all be slouching and moaning right now.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[204]:0,78
The last thing I remember was the Bradley being tossed like a Hot Wheels car.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[204]:78,156
I don’t know where the hit was, but I’m guessing it must have been close.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[204]:156,249
I’m sure had I still been standing out there, exposed, I wouldn’t be standing here today.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:0,56
Have you ever seen the effects of a thermobaric weapon?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:56,125
Have you ever asked anyone with stars on their shoulders about them?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:125,178
I bet my ballsack you’ll never get the full story.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:178,326
You’ll hear about heat and pressure, the fireball that continues expanding, exploding, and literally crushing and burning everything in its path.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:326,378
Heat and pressure, that’s what thermobaric means.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:378,406
Sounds nasty enough, right?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:406,522
What you won’t hear about is the immediate aftereffect, the vacuum created when that fireball suddenly contracts.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:522,696
Anyone left alive will either have the air sucked right out of their lungs, or—and they’ll never admit this to anyone—have their lungs ripped right out of their mouth.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:696,1041
Obviously no one’s going to live long enough to tell that kind of horror story, probably why the Pentagon’s been so good at covering up the truth, but if you ever see a picture of a G, or even an example of a real walking specimen, and he’s got both air bags and windpipe just dangling out from his lips, make sure you give him my number.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[205]:1041,1096
I’m always up for meeting another veteran of Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[206]
WorldWarZ
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[207]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[208]
ROBBEN ISLAND, CAPE TOWN PROVINCE, UNITED STATES OF SOUTHERN AFRICA
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[209]:0,139
[Xolelwa Azania greets me at his writing desk, inviting me to switch places with him so I can enjoy the cool ocean breeze from his window.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[209]:139,239
He apologizes for the “mess” and insists on clearing the notes off his desk before we continue.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[209]:239,327
Mister Azania is halfway through his third volume of Rainbow Fist: South Africa at War.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[209]:327,496
This volume happens to be about the subject we are discussing, the turning point against the living dead, the moment when his country pulled itself back from the brink.]
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[210]:0,96
Dispassionate, a rather mundane word to describe one of history’s most controversial figures.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[210]:96,412
Some revere him as a savior, some revile him as a monster, but if you ever met Paul Redeker, ever discussed his views of the world and the problems, or more importantly, the solutions to the problems that plague the world, probably the one word that would always cling to your impression of the man is dispassionate.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:0,132
Paul always believed, well, perhaps not always, but at least in his adult life, that humanity’s one fundamental flaw was emotion.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:132,259
He used to say that the heart should only exist to pump blood to the brain, that anything else was a waste of time and energy.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:259,440
His papers from university, all dealing with alternate “solutions” to historical, societal quandaries, were what first brought him to the attention of the apartheid government.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:440,681
Many psychobiographers have tried to label him a racist, but, in his own words, “racism is a regrettable by-product of irrational emotion.” Others have argued that, in order for a racist to hate one group, he must at least love another.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:681,735
Redeker believed both love and hate to be irrelevant.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:735,915
To him, they were “impediments of the human condition,” and, in his words again, “imagine what could be accomplished if the human race would only shed its humanity.” Evil?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[211]:915,1089
Most would call it that, while others, particularly that small cadre in the center of Pretoria’s power, believed it to be “an invaluable source of liberated intellect.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[212]:0,70
It was the early 1980s, a critical time for the apartheid government.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[212]:70,113
The country was resting on a bed of nails.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[212]:113,343
You had the ANC, you had the Inkatha Freedom Party, you even had extremist, right-wing elements of the Afrikaner population that would have liked nothing better than open revolt in order to bring about a complete racial showdown.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[212]:343,480
On her border, South Africa faced nothing but hostile nations, and, in the case of Angola, a Soviet-backed, Cuban-spearheaded civil war.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[212]:480,687
Add to this mixture a growing isolation from the Western democracies (which included a critical arms embargo) and it was no surprise that a last-ditch fight for survival was never far from Pretoria’s mind.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[213]:0,207
This is why they enlisted the aid of Mister Redeker to revise the government’s ultrasecret “Plan Orange.” “Orange” had been in existence since the apartheid government first came to power in 1948.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[213]:207,352
It was the doomsday scenario for the country’s white minority, the plan to deal with an all-out uprising of its indigenous African population.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[213]:352,438
Over the years it had been updated with the changing strategic outlook of the region.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[213]:438,491
Every decade that situation grew more and more grim.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[213]:491,764
With multiplying independence of her neighbor states, and multiplying voices for freedom from the majority of her own people, those in Pretoria realized that a full-blown confrontation might not just mean the end for the Afrikaner government, but the Afrikaners themselves.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[214]:0,34
This is where Redeker stepped in.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[214]:34,153
His revised Plan Orange, appropriately completed in 1984, was the ultimate survival strategy for the Afrikaner people.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[214]:153,178
No variable was ignored.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[214]:178,500
Population figures, terrain, resources, logistics…Redeker not only updated the plan to include both Cuba’s chemical weapons and his own country’s nuclear option, but also, and this is what made “Orange Eighty-Four” so historic, the determination of which Afrikaners would be saved and which had to be sacrificed.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[215]
Sacrificed?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[216]:0,151
Redeker believed that to try to protect everyone would stretch the government’s resources to the breaking point, thus dooming the entire population.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[216]:151,264
He compared it to survivors from a sinking ship capsizing a lifeboat that simply did not have room for them all.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[216]:264,493
Redeker had even gone so far as to calculate who should be “brought aboard.” He included income, IQ, fertility, an entire checklist of “desirable qualities,” including the subject’s location to a potential crisis zone.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[216]:493,658
“The first casualty of the conflict must be our own sentimentality” was the closing statement for his proposal, “for its survival will mean our destruction.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[217]:0,41
Orange Eighty-Four was a brilliant plan.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[217]:41,143
It was clear, logical, efficient, and it made Paul Redeker one of the most hated men in South Africa.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[217]:143,265
His first enemies were some of the more radical, fundamentalist Afrikaners, the racial ideologues and the ultrareligious.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[217]:265,358
Later, after the fall of apartheid, his name began circulating among the general population.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[217]:358,473
Of course he was invited to appear before the “Truth and Reconciliation” hearings, and, of course, he refused.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[217]:473,632
“I won’t pretend to have a heart simply to save my skin,” he stated publicly, adding, “No matter what I do, I’m sure they will come for me anyway.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:0,86
And they did, although it probably was not in the manner Redeker could have expected.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:86,157
It was during our Great Panic, which began several weeks before yours.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:157,272
Redeker was holed up in the Drakensberg cabin he had bought with the accumulated profits of a business consultant.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:272,301
He liked business, you know.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:301,342
“One goal, no soul,” he used to say.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:342,456
He wasn’t surprised when the door blew off its hinges and agents of the National Intelligence Agency rushed in.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:456,513
They confirmed his name, his identity, his past actions.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:513,589
They asked him point-blank if he had been the author of Orange Eighty-Four.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:589,629
He answered without emotion, naturally.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:629,796
He suspected, and accepted, this intrusion as a last-minute revenge killing; the world was going to hell anyway, why not take a few “apartheid devils” down first.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:796,926
What he could have never predicted was the sudden lowering of their firearms, and the removal of the gas masks of the NIA agents.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:926,1126
They were of all colors: black, Asian, colored, and even a white man, a tall Afrikaner who stepped forward, and without giving his name or rank, asked abruptly…“You’ve got a plan for this, man.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[218]:1126,1141
Don’t you?”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[219]:0,78
Redeker had, indeed, been working on his own solution to the undead epidemic.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[219]:78,127
What else could he do in this isolated hideaway?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[219]:127,216
It had been an intellectual exercise; he never believed anyone would be left to read it.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[219]:216,377
It had no name, as explained later “because names only exist to distinguish one from others,” and, until that moment, there had been no other plan like his.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[219]:377,562
Once again, Redeker had taken everything into account, not only the strategic situation of the country, but also the physiology, behavior, and “combat doctrine” of the living dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[219]:562,701
While you can research the details of the “Redeker Plan” in any public library around the world, here are some of the fundamental keys:
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[220]:0,49
First of all, there was no way to save everyone.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[220]:49,80
The outbreak was too far gone.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[220]:80,265
The armed forces had already been too badly weakened to effectively isolate the threat, and, spread so thinly throughout the country, they could only grow weaker with each passing day.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[220]:265,453
Our forces had to be consolidated, withdrawn to a special “safe zone,” which, hopefully, would be aided by some natural obstacle such as mountains, rivers, or even an offshore island.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[220]:453,657
Once concentrated within this zone, the armed forces could eradicate the infestation within its borders, then use what resources were available to defend it against further onslaughts of the living dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[220]:657,756
That was the first part of the plan and it made as much sense as any conventional military retreat.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[221]:0,136
The second part of the plan dealt with the evacuation of civilians, and this could not have been envisioned by anyone else but Redeker.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[221]:136,235
In his mind, only a small fraction of the civilian population could be evacuated to the safe zone.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[221]:235,505
These people would be saved not only to provide a labor pool for the eventual wartime economic restoration, but also to preserve the legitimacy and stability of the government, to prove to those already within the zone that their leaders were “looking out for them.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:0,197
There was another reason for this partial evacuation, an eminently logical and insidiously dark reason that, many believe, will forever ensure Redeker the tallest pedestal in the pantheon of hell.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:197,271
Those who were left behind were to be herded into special isolated zones.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:271,383
They were to be “human bait,” distracting the undead from following the retreating army to their safe zone.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:383,566
Redeker argued that these isolated, uninfected refugees must be kept alive, well defended and even resupplied, if possible, so as to keep the undead hordes firmly rooted to the spot.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:566,600
You see the genius, the sickness?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:600,973
Keeping people as prisoners because “every zombie besieging those survivors will be one less zombie throwing itself against our defenses.” That was the moment when the Afrikaner agent looked up at Redeker, crossed himself, and said, “God help you, man.” Another one said, “God help us all.” That was the black one who appeared to be in charge of the operation.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[222]:973,1011
“Now let’s get him out of here.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[223]:0,134
Within minutes they were on a helicopter for Kimberley, the very underground base where Redeker had first written Orange Eighty-Four.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[223]:134,249
He was ushered into a meeting of the president’s surviving cabinet, where his report was read aloud to the room.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[223]:249,335
You should have heard the uproar, with no voice louder than the defense minister’s.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[223]:335,434
He was a Zulu, a ferocious man who’d rather be fighting in the streets than cowering in a bunker.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[224]:0,62
The vice president was more concerned about public relations.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[224]:62,174
He didn’t want to imagine what his backside would be worth if news of this plan ever leaked to the population.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[225]:0,60
The president looked almost personally insulted by Redeker.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[225]:60,206
He physically grabbed the lapels of the safety and security minister and demanded why in hell he brought him this demented apartheid war criminal.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[226]
The minister stammered that he didn’t understand why the president was so upset, especially when it was he who gave the order to find Redeker.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[227]
The president threw his hands in the air and shouted that he never gave such an order, and then, from somewhere in the room, a faint voice said, “I did.”
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:0,161
He had been sitting against the back wall; now he stood, hunched over by age, and supported by canes, but with a spirit as strong and vital as it had ever been.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:161,381
The elder statesman, the father of our new democracy, the man whose birth name had been Rolihlahla, which some have translated simply into “Troublemaker.” As he stood, all others sat, all others except Paul Redeker.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:381,933
The old man locked eyes on him, smiled with that warm squint so famous the world over, and said, “Molo, mhlobo wam.” “Greetings, person of my region.” He walked slowly over to Paul, turned to the governing body of South Africa, then lifted the pages from the Afrikaner’s hand and said in a suddenly loud and youthful voice, “This plan will save our people.” Then, gesturing to Paul, he said, “This man will save our people.” And then came that moment, the one that historians will probably debate until the subject fades from memory.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:933,966
He embraced the white Afrikaner.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:966,1132
To anyone else this was simply his signature bear hug, but to Paul Redeker…I know that the majority of psychobiographers continue to paint this man without a soul.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1132,1171
That is the generally accepted notion.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1171,1223
Paul Redeker: no feelings, no compassion, no heart.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1223,1422
However, one of our most revered authors, Biko’s old friend and biographer, postulates that Redeker was actually a deeply sensitive man, too sensitive, in fact, for life in apartheid South Africa.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1422,1581
He insists that Redeker’s lifelong jihad against emotion was the only way to protect his sanity from the hatred and brutality he witnessed on a daily basis.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1581,1738
Not much is known about Redeker’s childhood, whether he even had parents, or was raised by the state, whether he had friends or was ever loved in any way.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1738,1867
Those who knew him from work were hard-pressed to remember witnessing any social interaction or even any physical act of warmth.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[228]:1867,1960
The embrace by our nation’s father, this genuine emotion piercing his impenetrable shell…
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[229]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[230]
[Azania smiles sheepishly.]
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[231]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:0,37
Perhaps this is all too sentimental.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:37,135
For all we know he was a heartless monster, and the old man’s embrace had absolutely no impact.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:135,211
But I can tell you that that was the last day anyone ever saw Paul Redeker.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:211,263
Even now, no one knows what really happened to him.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:263,375
That is when I stepped in, in those chaotic weeks when the Redeker Plan was implemented throughout the country.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:375,625
It took some convincing to say the least, but once I’d convinced them that I’d worked for many years with Paul Redeker, and, more importantly, I understood his way of thinking better than anyone left alive in South Africa, how could they refuse?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:625,738
I worked on the retreat, then afterward, during the consolidation months, and right up until the end of the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:738,846
At least they were appreciative of my services, why else would they grant me such luxurious accommodations?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:846,892
[Smiles.] Paul Redeker, an angel and a devil.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:892,925
Some hate him, some worship him.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:925,946
Me, I just pity him.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[232]:946,1027
If he still exists, somewhere out there, I sincerely hope he’s found his peace.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[233]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[234]:0,87
[After a parting embrace from my guest, I am driven back to my ferry for the mainland.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[234]:87,138
Security is tight as I sign out my entrance badge.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[234]:138,185
The tall Afrikaner guard photographs me again.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[234]:185,249
“Can’t be too careful, man,” he says, handing me the pen.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[234]:249,389
“Lot of people out there want to send him to hell.” I sign next to my name, under the heading of Robben Island Psychiatric Institution.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[234]:389,437
NAME OF PATIENT YOU ARE VISITING: PAUL REDEKER.]
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[235]
ARMAGH, IRELAND
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[236]:0,111
[While not a Catholic himself, Philip Adler has joined the throngs of visitors to the pope’s wartime refuge.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[236]:111,175
“My wife is Bavarian,” he explains in the bar of our hotel.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[236]:175,311
“She had to make the pilgrimage to Saint Patrick’s Cathedral.” This is his first time away from Germany since the end of the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[236]:311,338
Our meeting is accidental.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[236]:338,373
He does not object to my recorder.]
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[237]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:0,30
Hamburg was heavily infested.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:30,110
They were in the streets, in the buildings, pouring out of the Neuer Elbtunnel.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:110,266
We’d tried to blockade it with civilian vehicles, but they were squirming through any open space like bloated, bloody worms. Refugees were also all over.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:266,343
They’d come from as far away as Saxony, thinking they could escape by sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:343,390
The ships were long gone, the port was a mess.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:390,501
We had over a thousand trapped at the Reynolds Aluminiumwerk and at least triple that at the Eurokai terminal.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[238]:501,629
No food, no clean water, just waiting to be rescued with the dead swarming outside, and I don’t know how many infected inside.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[239]:0,72
The harbor was choked with corpses, but corpses that were still moving.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[239]:72,192
We’d blasted them into the harbor with antiriot water cannons; it saved ammo and it helped to keep the streets clear.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[239]:192,253
It was a good idea, until the pressure in the hydrants died.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[239]:253,323
We’d lost our commanding officer two days earlier…freak accident.
====
