Dad came back in, his face was white.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[316]:712,744
I never asked him what happened.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[317]:0,76
The only time anyone ever came together was when one of the dead showed up.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[317]:76,161
These were the ones who’d followed the third wave, coming alone or in small packs.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[317]:161,195
It happened every couple of days.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[317]:195,267
Someone would sound an alarm and everyone would rally to take them out.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[317]:267,337
And then, as soon as it was over, we’d all turn on each other again.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[318]
When it got cold enough to freeze the lake, when the last of the dead stopped showing up, a lot of people thought it was safe enough to try to walk home.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[319]:0,6
Walk?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[319]:6,16
Not drive?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[320]:0,13
No more gas.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[320]:13,97
They’d used it all up for cooking fuel or just to keep their car heaters running.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[320]:97,291
Every day there’d be these groups of half-starved, ragged wretches, all loaded down with all this useless stuff they’d brought with them, all with this look of desperate hope on their faces.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[321]:0,58
“Where do they think they’re going?” Dad would say.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[321]:58,130
“Don’t they know that it hasn’t gotten cold enough farther south?
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[321]:130,291
Don’t they know what’s still waiting for them back there?” He was convinced that if we just held out long enough, sooner or later things would get better.
====
/html/body/div/div[5]/p[321]:291,351
That was in October, when I still looked like a human being.
