====
/html/body/div/p[11]:980,1064
I found out later that Mrs. Magda Antonova used to be this woman’s cleaning lady.
====
/html/body/div/p[11]:1064,1239
Yes, it was very hard for some, but a lot of them later admitted that they got more emotional satisfaction from their new jobs than anything closely resembling their old ones.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:0,65
I met one gentleman on a coastal ferry from Portland to Seattle.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:65,231
He had worked in the licensing department for an advertising agency, specifically in charge of procuring the rights to classic rock songs for television commercials.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:231,259
Now he was a chimney sweep.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:259,384
Given that most homes in Seattle had lost their central heat and the winters were now longer and colder, he was seldom idle.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:384,438
“I help keep my neighbors warm,” he said proudly.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:438,528
I know it sounds a little too Norman Rockwell, but I hear stories like that all the time.
====
/html/body/div/p[12]:528,634
