====
/html/body/div/p[29]:0,52
Ask anyone how the Allies won the Second World War.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:52,138
Those with very little knowledge might answer that it was our numbers or generalship.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:138,225
Those without any knowledge might point to techno-marvels like radar or the atom bomb.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:225,658
[Scowls.] Anyone with the most rudimentary understanding of that conflict will give you three real reasons: first, the ability to manufacture more materiel: more bullets, beans, and bandages than the enemy; second, the natural resources available to manufacture that materiel; and third, the logistical means to not only transport those resources to the factories, but also to transport the finished products out to the front lines.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:658,733
The Allies had the resources, industry, and logistics of an entire planet.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:733,840
The Axis, on the other hand, had to depend on what scant assets they could scrape up within their borders.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:840,868
This time we were the Axis.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:868,1047
The living dead controlled most of the world’s landmass, while American war production depended on what could be harvested within the limits of the western states specifically.
====
/html/body/div/p[29]:1047,1205
Forget raw materials from safe zones overseas; our merchant fleet was crammed to the decks with refugees while fuel shortages had dry-docked most of our navy.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:0,24
We had some advantages.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:24,134
California’s agricultural base could at least erase the problem of starvation, if it could be restructured.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:134,200
The citrus growers didn’t go quietly, neither did the ranchers.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:200,280
The beef barons who controlled so much prime potential farmland were the worst.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:280,311
Did you ever hear of Don Hill?
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:311,353
Ever see the movie Roy Elliot did on him?
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:353,511
It was when the infestation hit the San Joaquin Valley, the dead swarming over his fences, attacking his cattle, tearing them apart like African driver ants.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:511,614
And there he was in the middle of it all, shooting and hollering like Gregory Peck in Duel in the Sun.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:614,652
I dealt with him openly and honestly.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:652,698
As with everyone else, I gave him the choice.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:698,796
I reminded him that winter was coming and there were still a lot of very hungry people out there.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:796,950
I warned him that when the hordes of starving refugees showed up to finish what the living dead started, he’d have no government protection whatsoever.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:950,1012
Hill was a brave, stubborn bastard, but he wasn’t an idiot.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:1012,1141
He agreed to surrender his land and herd only on the condition that his and everyone else’s breeding stock remained untouched.
====
/html/body/div/p[30]:1141,1158
We shook on that.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:0,99
Tender, juicy steaks—can you think of a better icon of our prewar artificial standard of living?
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:99,176
And yet it was that standard that ended up being our second great advantage.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:176,236
The only way to supplement our resource base was recycling.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:236,258
This was nothing new.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:258,382
The Israelis had started when they sealed their borders and since then each nation had adopted it to one degree or another.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:382,468
None of their stockpiles, however, could even compare to what we had at our disposal.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:468,522
Think about what life was like in the prewar America.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:522,682
Even those considered middle class enjoyed, or took for granted, a level of material comfort unheard of by any other nation at any other time in human history.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:682,835
The clothing, the kitchenware, the electronics, the automobiles, just in the Los Angeles basin alone, outnumbered the prewar population by three to one.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:835,904
The cars poured in by the millions, every house, every neighborhood.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:904,1119
We had an entire industry of over a hundred thousand employees working three shifts, seven days a week: collecting, cataloging, disassembling, storing, and shipping parts and pieces to factories all over the coast.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:1119,1267
There was a little trouble, like with the cattle ranchers, people not wanting to turn over their Hummers or vintage Italian midlife crisis mobiles.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:1267,1324
Funny, no gas to run them but they still hung on anyway.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:1324,1356
It didn’t bother me too much.
====
/html/body/div/p[31]:1356,1429
They were a pleasure to deal with compared to the military establishment.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:0,75
Of all my adversaries, easily the most tenacious were the ones in uniform.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:75,177
I never had direct control over any of their R&D, they were free to green light whatever they wanted.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:177,354
But given that almost all their programs were farmed out to civilian contractors and that those contractors depended on resources controlled by DeStRes, I had de facto control.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:354,418
“You cannot mothball our Stealth bombers,” they would yell.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:418,568
“Who the Blank do you think you are to cancel our production of tanks?” At first I tried to reason with them: “The M-1 Abrams has a jet engine.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:568,615
Where are you going to find that kind of fuel?
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:615,901
Why do you need Stealth aircraft against an enemy that doesn’t have radar?” I tried to make them see that given what we had to work with, as opposed to what we were facing, we simply had to get the largest return on our investment or, in their language, the most bang for our buck.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:901,1004
They were insufferable, with their all-hours phone calls, or just showing up at my office unannounced.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:1004,1182
I guess I can’t really blame them, not after how we all treated them after the last brushfire war, and certainly not after almost having their asses handed to them at Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/p[32]:1182,1281
They were teetering on the edge of total collapse, and a lot of them just needed somewhere to vent.
