The “M” in MTHEL’s “Mobile” really meant a convoy of specialized vehicles, all of which were delicate, none truly all-terrain and each one completely dependent on the other.
====
/html/body/div/p[176]:200,330
MTHEL also required both tremendous power and copious amounts of highly unstable, highly toxic chemicals for the lasering process.
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:0,35
Zeus was a little more economical.
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:35,149
It was easier to cool, easier to maintain, and because it was Humvee-mounted, it could go anywhere it was needed.
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:149,190
The problem was, why would it be needed?
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:190,307
Even on high power, the gunner still had to hold a beam in place, on a moving target, mind you, for several seconds.
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:307,389
A good sharpshooter could get the job done in half the time with twice the kills.
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:389,483
That erased the potential for rapid fire, which was exactly what you needed in swarm attacks.
====
/html/body/div/p[177]:483,620
In fact, both units had a squad of riflemen permanently assigned to them, people protecting a machine that is designed to protect people.
====
/html/body/div/p[178]
They were that bad?
====
/html/body/div/p[179]:0,29
Not for their original role.
====
/html/body/div/p[179]:29,179
MTHEL kept Israel safe from terrorist bombardment, and Zeus actually came out of retirement to clear unexploded ordnance during the army’s advance.
====
/html/body/div/p[179]:179,228
As purpose-built weapons, they were outstanding.
====
/html/body/div/p[179]:228,271
As zombie killers, they were hopeless duds.
====
/html/body/div/p[180]
So why did you film them?
====
/html/body/div/p[181]:0,38
Because Americans worship technology.
====
/html/body/div/p[181]:38,90
It’s an inherent trait in the national zeitgeist.
====
/html/body/div/p[181]:90,200
Whether we realize it or not, even the most indefatigable Luddite can’t deny our country’s technoprowess.
====
/html/body/div/p[181]:200,367
We split the atom, we reached the moon, we’ve filled every household and business with more gadgets and gizmos than early sci-fi writers could have ever dreamed of.
====
/html/body/div/p[181]:367,436
I don’t know if that’s a good thing, I’m in no place to judge.
====
/html/body/div/p[181]:436,570
But I do know that just like all those ex-atheists in foxholes, most Americans were still praying for the God of science to save them.
====
/html/body/div/p[182]
But it didn’t.
====
/html/body/div/p[183]:0,24
But it didn’t matter.
====
/html/body/div/p[183]:24,88
The movie was such a hit that I was asked to do a whole series.
====
/html/body/div/p[183]:88,272
I called it “Wonder Weapons,” seven films on our military’s cutting-edge technology, none of which made any strategic difference, but all of which were psychological war winners.
====
/html/body/div/p[184]
Isn’t that…
