====
/html/body/div/p[202]
Would you say this was a common feeling?
====
/html/body/div/p[203]:0,108
Let me put it this way; the Russian army wasn’t the only service to be decimated by their own government.
====
/html/body/div/p[203]:108,178
The Armed Forces Reconstruction Act basically neutered the air force.
====
/html/body/div/p[203]:178,304
Some DeStRes “experts” had determined that our resource-to-kill ratio, our RKR, was the most lopsided of all the branches.
====
/html/body/div/p[204]
Could you give me some example?
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:0,47
How about the JSOW, the Joint Standoff Weapon?
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:47,158
It was a gravity bomb, guided by GPS and Inertial Nav, that could be released from as far as forty miles away.
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:158,390
The baseline version carried one hundred and forty BLU-97B submunitions, and each bomblet carried a shaped charge against armored targets, a fragmented case against infantry, and a zirconium ring to set the entire kill zone ablaze.
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:390,439
It had been considered a triumph, until Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:439,703
1 Now we were told that the price of one JSOW kit—the materials, manpower, time, and energy, not to mention the fuel and ground maintenance needed for the delivery aircraft—could pay for a platoon of infantry pukes who could smoke a thousand times as many Gs.
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:703,774
Not enough bang for our buck, like so many of our former crown jewels.
====
/html/body/div/p[205]:774,821
They went through us like an industrial laser.
