/html/body/div/p[216]
 
====
/html/body/div/p[217]:0,28
Islands in the Sea of Zack.
====
/html/body/div/p[217]:28,70
Green denotes active military facilities.
====
/html/body/div/p[217]:70,124
Some of them had been converted into refugee centers.
====
/html/body/div/p[217]:124,172
Some were still contributing to the war effort.
====
/html/body/div/p[217]:172,224
Some were well defended but had no strategic impact.
====
/html/body/div/p[218]:0,85
The Red Zones were labeled “Offensively Viable”: factories, mines, power plants.
====
/html/body/div/p[218]:85,144
The army’d left custodial teams during the big pullback.
====
/html/body/div/p[218]:144,263
Their job was to guard and maintain these facilities for a time when, if, we could add them to the overall war effort.
====
/html/body/div/p[218]:263,432
The Blue Zones were civilian areas where people had managed to make a stand, carve out a little piece of real estate, and figure some way to live within its boundaries.
====
/html/body/div/p[218]:432,535
All these zones were in need of resupply and that’s what the “Continental Airlift” was all about.
====
/html/body/div/p[219]:0,94
It was a massive operation, not just in terms of aircraft and fuel, but organization as well.
====
/html/body/div/p[219]:94,328
Remaining in contact with all these islands, processing their demands, coordinating with DeStRes, then trying to procure and prioritize all the materiel for each drop made it the statistically largest undertaking in air force history.
====
/html/body/div/p[220]:0,104
We tried to stay away from consumables, things like food and medicine that required regular deliveries.
====
/html/body/div/p[220]:104,264
These were classified as DDs, dependency drops, and they got a backseat to SSDs, self-sustaining drops, like tools, spare parts, and tools to make spare parts.
====
/html/body/div/p[220]:264,474
“They don’t need fish,” Sinclair used to say, “they need fishing poles.” Still, every autumn, we dropped a lot of fish, and wheat, and salt, and dried vegetables and baby formula…Winters were hard.
====
/html/body/div/p[220]:474,509
Remember how long they used to be?
====
/html/body/div/p[220]:509,600
Helping people to help themselves is great in theory, but you still gotta keep ’em alive.
====
/html/body/div/p[221]:0,152
Sometimes you had to drop in people, specialists like doctors or engineers, people with the kind of training you just can’t get from a how-to manual.
====
/html/body/div/p[221]:152,336
The Blue Zones got a lot of Special Forces instructors, not only to teach them how better to defend themselves, but to prepare them for the day they might have to go on the offensive.
====
/html/body/div/p[221]:336,376
I have a lot of respect for those guys.
====
/html/body/div/p[221]:376,524
Most of them knew it was for the duration; a lot of the Blue Zones didn’t have airstrips, so they had to parachute in without any hope of pickup.
====
