It had been discovered in the 1990s but never exploited for a variety of political and environmental reasons.
====
/html/body/div/p[354]:282,323
You can believe we exploited it, though.
====
/html/body/div/p[354]:323,438
Our contingent of royal engineers rigged a scaffolding up and over our wall, and extended it to the drilling site.
====
/html/body/div/p[354]:438,539
It was quite an achievement, and you can see how it became the precursor to our fortified motorways.
====
/html/body/div/p[354]:539,660
On a personal level, I was just grateful for the warm rooms, hot food, and, in a pinch…the Molotovs and flaming ditch.
====
/html/body/div/p[354]:660,928
It’s not the most efficient way to stop a Zed Head, I know, but as long as you’ve got them stuck and can keep them in the fire…and besides, what else could we do when the bullets ran out and we were left with nothing else but an odd lot of medieval hand weapons?
====
/html/body/div/p[355]:0,111
There were quite a bit of those about, in museums, personal collections…and not a decorative dud among them.
====
/html/body/div/p[355]:111,146
These were real, tough and tested.
====
/html/body/div/p[355]:146,272
They became part of British life again, ordinary citizens traipsing about with a mace or halberd or double-bladed battle-axe.
====
/html/body/div/p[355]:272,371
I myself became rather adept with this claymore, although you wouldn’t think of it to look at me.
====
/html/body/div/p[356]
 
====
/html/body/div/p[357]
[He gestures, slightly embarrassed, to the weapon almost as long as himself.]
====
/html/body/div/p[358]
 
====
/html/body/div/p[359]
It’s not really ideal, takes a lot of skill, but eventually you learn what you can do, what you never thought you were capable of, what others around you are capable of.
====
/html/body/div/p[360]
 
