====
/html/body/div/p[366]
No, please, it’s quite all right.
====
/html/body/div/p[367]:0,55
[Takes a breath.] She…she wouldn’t leave, you see.
====
/html/body/div/p[367]:55,239
She insisted, over the objections of Parliament, to remain at Windsor, as she put it, “for the duration.” I thought maybe it was misguided nobility, or maybe fear-based paralysis.
====
/html/body/div/p[367]:239,302
I tried to make her see reason, begged her almost on my knees.
====
/html/body/div/p[367]:302,439
Hadn’t she done enough with the Balmoral Decree, turning all her estates into protected zones for any who could reach and defend them?
====
/html/body/div/p[367]:439,598
Why not join her family in Ireland or the Isle of Man, or, at least, if she was insisting on remaining in Britain, supreme command HQ north above the Antonine.
====
/html/body/div/p[368]
What did she say?
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:0,385
“The highest of distinctions is service to others.” [He clears his throat, his upper lip quivers for a second.] Her father had said that; it was the reason he had refused to run to Canada during the Second World War, the reason her mother had spent the blitz visiting civilians huddled in the tube stations beneath London, the same reason, to this day, we remain a United Kingdom.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:385,470
Their task, their mandate, is to personify all that is great in our national spirit.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:470,574
They must forever be an example to the rest of us, the strongest, and bravest, and absolute best of us.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:574,746
In a sense, it is they who are ruled by us, instead of the other way around, and they must sacrifice everything, everything, to shoulder the weight of this godlike burden.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:746,785
Otherwise what’s the flipping point?
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:785,886
Just scrap the whole damn tradition, roll out the bloody guillotine, and be done with it altogether.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:886,1033
They were viewed very much like castles, I suppose: as crumbling, obsolete relics, with no real modern function other than as tourist attractions.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:1033,1132
But when the skies darkened and the nation called, both reawoke to the meaning of their existence.
====
/html/body/div/p[369]:1132,1178
One shielded our bodies, the other, our souls.
====
/html/body/div/p[370]
ULITHI ATOLL, FEDERATED STATES OF MICRONESIA
====
/html/body/div/p[371]:0,113
[During World War II, this vast coral atoll served as the main forward base for the United States Pacific Fleet.
====
/html/body/div/p[371]:113,219
During World War Z, it sheltered not only American naval vessels, but hundreds of civilian ships as well.
====
/html/body/div/p[371]:219,301
One of those ships was the UNS Ural, the first broadcast hub of Radio Free Earth.
====
/html/body/div/p[371]:301,408
Now a museum to the achievements of the project, she is the focus of the British documentary Words at War.
====
/html/body/div/p[371]:408,482
One of the subjects interviewed for this documentary is Barati Palshigar.]
====
/html/body/div/p[372]
 
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:0,25
Ignorance was the enemy.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:25,80
Lies and superstition, misinformation, disinformation.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:80,114
Sometimes, no information at all.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:114,151
Ignorance killed billions of people.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:151,184
Ignorance caused the Zombie War.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:184,231
Imagine if we had known then what we know now.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:231,309
Imagine if the undead virus had been as understood as, say, tuberculosis was.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:309,443
Imagine if the world’s citizens, or at least those charged with protecting those citizens, had known exactly what they were facing.
====
/html/body/div/p[373]:443,511
Ignorance was the real enemy, and cold, hard facts were the weapons.
====
/html/body/div/p[374]:0,119
When I first joined Radio Free Earth, it was still called the International Program for Health and Safety Information.
====
/html/body/div/p[374]:119,223
The title “Radio Free Earth” came from the individuals and communities who monitored our broadcasts.
====
/html/body/div/p[375]:0,140
It was the first real international venture, barely a few months after the South African Plan, and years before the conference at Honolulu.
====
/html/body/div/p[375]:140,256
Just like the rest of the world based their survival strategies on Redeker, our genesis was routed in Radio Ubunye.
====
/html/body/div/p[375]:256,257
1
====
/html/body/div/p[376]
What was Radio Ubunye?
====
/html/body/div/p[377]:0,54
South Africa’s broadcasts to its isolated citizens.
====
/html/body/div/p[377]:54,178
Because they didn’t have the resources for material aid, the only assistance the government could render was information.
====
/html/body/div/p[377]:178,275
They were the first, at least, to my knowledge, to begin these regular, multilingual broadcasts.
====
/html/body/div/p[377]:275,428
Not only did they offer practical survival skills, they went so far as to collect and address each and every falsehood circulating among their citizens.
====
/html/body/div/p[377]:428,516
What we did was take the template of Radio Ubunye and adapt it for the global community.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:0,107
I came aboard, literally, at the very beginning, as the Ural’s reactors were just being put back online.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:107,183
The Ural was a former vessel of the Soviet, then the Russian, Federal Navy.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:183,318
Back then the SSV-33 had been many things: a command and control ship, a missile tracking platform, an electronic surveillance vessel.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:318,443
Unfortunately, she was also a white elephant, because her systems, they tell me, were too complicated even for her own crew.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:443,586
She had spent the majority of her career tied to a pier at the Vladivostok naval base, providing additional electrical power for the facility.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:586,765
I am not an engineer, so I don’t how they managed to replace her spent fuel rods or convert her massive communication facilities to interface with the global satellite network.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:765,839
I specialize in languages, specifically those of the Indian Subcontinent.
====
/html/body/div/p[378]:839,955
Myself and Mister Verma, just the two of us to cover a billion people…well…at that point it was still a billion.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:0,60
Mister Verma had found me in the refugee camp in Sri Lanka.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:60,103
He was a translator, I was an interpreter.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:103,185
We had worked together several years before at our country’s embassy in London.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:185,240
We thought it had been hard work then; we had no idea.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:240,306
It was a maddening grind, eighteen, sometimes twenty hours a day.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:306,336
I don’t know when we slept.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:336,406
There was so much raw data, so many dispatches arriving every minute.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:406,545
Much of it had to do with basic survival: how to purify water, create an indoor greenhouse, culture and process mold spore for penicillin.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:545,649
This mind-numbing copy would often be punctuated with facts and terms that I had never heard of before.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:649,783
I’d never heard the term “quisling” or “feral”; I didn’t know what a “Lobo” was or the false miracle cure of Phalanx.
====
/html/body/div/p[379]:783,968
All I knew was that suddenly there was a uniformed man shoving a collection of words before my eyes and telling me “We need this in Marathi, and ready to record in fifteen minutes.”
====
/html/body/div/p[380]
What kind of misinformation were you combating?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:0,31
Where do you want me to begin?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:31,40
Medical?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:40,52
Scientific?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:52,62
Military?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:62,73
Spiritual?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:73,88
Psychological?
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:88,141
The psychological aspect I found the most maddening.
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:141,204
People wanted so badly to anthropomorphize the walking blight.
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:204,330
In war, in a conventional war that is, we spend so much time trying to dehumanize the enemy, to create an emotional distance.
====
/html/body/div/p[381]:330,619
We would make up stories or derogatory titles…when I think about what my father used to call Muslims…and now in this war it seemed that everyone was trying desperately to find some shred of a connection to their enemy, to put a human face on something that was so unmistakably inhuman.
====
/html/body/div/p[382]
Can you give me some examples?
====
/html/body/div/p[383]:0,254
There were so many misconceptions: zombies were somehow intelligent; they could feel and adapt, use tools and even some human weapons; they carried memories of their former existence; or they could be communicated with and trained like some kind of pet.
====
/html/body/div/p[383]:254,327
It was heartbreaking, having to debunk one misguided myth after another.
====
/html/body/div/p[383]:327,394
The civilian survival guide helped, but was still severely limited.
====
/html/body/div/p[384]
Oh really?
====
/html/body/div/p[385]:0,8
Oh yes.
====
/html/body/div/p[385]:8,248
You could see it was clearly written by an American, the references to SUVs and personal firearms. There was no taking into account the cultural differences…the various indigenous solutions people believed would save them from the undead.
====
/html/body/div/p[386]
Such as?
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:0,138
I’d rather not give too many details, not without tacitly condemning the entire people group from which this “solution” originated.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:138,236
As an Indian, I had to deal with many aspects of my own culture that had turned self-destructive.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:236,417
There was Varanasi, one of the oldest cities on Earth, near the place where Buddha supposedly preached his first sermon and where thousands of Hindu pilgrims came each year to die.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:417,488
In normal, prewar conditions, the road would be littered with corpses.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:488,529
Now these corpses were rising to attack.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:529,599
Varanasi was one of the hottest White Zones, a nexus of living death.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:599,658
This nexus covered almost the entire length of the Ganges.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:658,796
Its healing powers had been scientifically assessed decades before the war, something to do with the high oxygenation rate of the waters.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:796,806
2 Tragic.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:806,871
Millions flocked to its shores, serving only to feed the flames.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:871,1017
Even after the government’s withdrawal to the Himalayas, when over 90 percent of the country was officially overrun, the pilgrimages continued.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1017,1052
Every country had a similar story.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1052,1180
Every one of our international crew had at least one moment when they were forced to confront an example of suicidal ignorance.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1180,1374
An American told us about how the religious sect known as “God’s Lambs” believed that the rapture had finally come and the quicker they were infected, the quicker they would go to heaven.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1374,1684
Another woman—I won’t say what country she belonged to—tried her best to dispel the notion that sexual intercourse with a virgin could “cleanse” the “curse.” I don’t know how many women, or little girls, were raped as a result of this “cleansing.” Everyone was furious with his own people.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1684,1706
Everyone was ashamed.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1706,1769
Our one Belgian crewmember compared it to the darkening skies.
====
/html/body/div/p[387]:1769,1826
He used to call it “the evil of our collective soul.”
====
/html/body/div/p[388]:0,37
I guess I have no right to complain.
====
/html/body/div/p[388]:37,92
My life was never in danger, my belly was always full.
====
/html/body/div/p[388]:92,162
I might not have slept often but at least I could sleep without fear.
====
/html/body/div/p[388]:162,234
Most importantly, I never had had to work in the Ural’s IR department.
====
/html/body/div/p[389]
IR?
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:0,23
Information Reception.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:23,88
The data we were broadcasting did not originate aboard the Ural.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:88,186
It came from all around the world, from experts and think tanks in various government safe zones.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:186,282
They would transmit their findings to our IR operators who, in turn, would pass it along to us.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:282,441
Much of this data was transmitted to us over conventional, open, civilian bands, and many of these bands were crammed with ordinary people’s cries for help.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:441,661
There were millions of wretched souls scattered throughout our planet, all screaming into their private radio sets as their children starved or their temporary fortress burned, or the living dead overran their defenses.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:661,793
Even if you didn’t understand the language, as many of the operators didn’t, there was no mistaking the human voice of anguish.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:793,861
They weren’t allowed to answer back, either; there wasn’t time.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:861,919
All transmissions had to be devoted to official business.
====
/html/body/div/p[390]:919,982
I don’t want to know what that was like for the IR operators.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:0,149
When the last broadcast came from Buenos Aires, when that famous Latin singer played that Spanish lullaby, it was too much for one of our operators.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:149,217
He wasn’t from Buenos Aires, he wasn’t even from South America.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:217,315
He was just an eighteen-year-old Russian sailor who blew his brains out all over his instruments.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:315,412
He was the first, and since the end of the war, the rest of the IR operators have followed suit.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:412,444
Not one of them is alive today.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:444,476
The last was my Belgian friend.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:476,539
“You carry those voices with you,” he told me one morning.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:539,647
We were standing on the deck, looking into that brown haze, waiting for a sunrise we knew we’d never see.
====
/html/body/div/p[391]:647,769
“Those cries will be with me the rest of my life, never resting, never fading, never ceasing their call to join them.”
====
/html/body/div/p[392]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[6]/p
World War Z
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[1]
THE DEMILITARIZED ZONE: SOUTH KOREA
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[2]:0,141
[Hyungchol Choi, deputy director of the Korean Central Intelligence Agency, gestures to the dry, hilly, unremarkable landscape to our north.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[2]:141,298
One might mistake it for Southern California, if not for the deserted pillboxes, fading banners, and rusting, barbed wire fence that runs to either horizon.]
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[3]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[4]:0,15
What happened?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[4]:15,29
No one knows.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[4]:29,103
No country was better prepared to repel the infestation than North Korea.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[4]:103,255
Rivers to the north, oceans to the east and west, and to the south [he gestures to the Demilitarized Zone], the most heavily fortified border on Earth.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[4]:255,438
You can see how mountainous the terrain is, how easily defensible, but what you can’t see is that those mountains are honeycombed with a titanic military-industrial infrastructure.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[4]:438,675
The North Korean government learned some very hard lessons from your bombing campaign of the 1950s and had been laboring ever since to create a subterranean system that would allow their people to wage another war from a secure location.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[5]:0,113
Their population was heavily militarized, marshaled to a degree of readiness that made Israel look like Iceland.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[5]:113,199
Over a million men and women were actively under arms with a further five in reserve.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[5]:199,378
That is over a quarter of the entire population, not to mention the fact that almost everyone in the country had, at some point in their lives, undergone basic military training.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[5]:378,521
More important than this training, though, and most important for this kind of warfare was an almost superhuman degree of national discipline.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[5]:521,691
North Koreans were indoctrinated from birth to believe that their lives were meaningless, that they existed only to serve the State, the Revolution, and the Great Leader.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:0,71
This is almost the polar opposite of what we experienced in the South.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:71,96
We were an open society.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:96,110
We had to be.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:110,149
International trade was our lifeblood.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:149,277
We were individualists, maybe not as much as you Americans, but we had more than our share of protests and public disturbances.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:277,400
We were such a free and fractured society that we barely managed to implement the Chang Doctrine 1 during the Great Panic.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:400,473
That kind of internal crisis would have been inconceivable in the North.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:473,636
They were a people who, even when their government caused a near genocidal famine, would rather resort to eating children 2 than raise even a whisper of defiance.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:636,711
This was the kind of subservience Adolf Hitler could have only dreamed of.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:711,907
If you had given each citizen a gun, a rock, or even their bare hands, pointed them at approaching zombies and said “Fight!” they would have done so down to the oldest woman and smallest tot.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:907,998
This was a country bred for war, planned, prepared, and poised for it since July 27, 1953.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[6]:998,1161
If you were going to invent a country to not only survive but triumph over the apocalypse we faced, it would have been the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[7]:0,18
So what happened?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[7]:18,184
About a month before our troubles started, before the first outbreaks were reported in Pusan, the North suddenly, and inexplicably, severed all diplomatic relations.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[7]:184,440
We weren’t told why the rail line, the only overland link between our two sides, was suddenly closed, or why some of our citizens who’d been waiting decades to see long lost relatives in the North had their dreams abruptly shattered by a rubber stamp.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[7]:440,478
No explanation of any kind was given.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[7]:478,549
All we got was their standard “matter of state security” brush-off.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:0,73
Unlike many others, I wasn’t convinced that this was a prelude to war.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:73,150
Whenever the North had threatened violence, they always rang the same bells.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:150,219
No satellite data, ours or the Americans, showed any hostile intent.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:219,304
There were no troop movements, no aircraft fueling, no ship or submarine deployment.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:304,409
If anything, our forces along the Demilitarized Zone began noticing their opposite numbers disappearing.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:409,446
We knew them all, the border troops.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:446,620
We’d photographed each one over the years, given them nicknames like Snake Eyes or Bulldog, even compiled dossiers on their supposed ages, backgrounds, and personal lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[8]:620,686
Now they were gone, vanished behind shielded trenches and dugouts.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[9]:0,46
Our seismic indicators were similarly silent.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[9]:46,199
If the North had begun tunneling operations or even massed vehicles on the other side of “Z,” we would have heard it like the National Opera Company.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:0,102
Panmunjom is the only area along the DMZ where opposing sides can meet for face-to-face negotiations.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:102,227
We share joint custody of the conference rooms, and our troops posture for each other over several meters of open courtyard.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:227,272
The guards were changed on a rotating basis.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:272,376
One night, as the North Korean detachment marched into their barracks, no replacement unit marched out.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:376,397
The doors were shut.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:397,427
The lights were extinguished.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[10]:427,455
And we never saw them again.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[11]:0,64
We also saw a complete halt to human intelligence infiltration.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[11]:64,140
Spies from the North were almost as regular and predictable as the seasons.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[11]:140,275
Most of the time they were easy to spot, wearing out-of-date clothes or asking the price of goods that they should have already known.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[11]:275,379
We used to pick them up all the time, but since the outbreaks began, their numbers had dwindled to zero.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[12]
What about your spies in the North?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[13]:0,99
Vanished, all of them, right about the same time all our electronic surveillance assets went dark.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[13]:99,189
I don’t mean there was no disturbing radio traffic, I mean there was no traffic at all.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[13]:189,261
One by one, all the civilian and military channels began shutting down.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[13]:261,469
Satellite images showed fewer farmers in their fields, less foot traffic in city streets, even fewer “volunteer” laborers on many public works projects, which is something that has never happened before.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[13]:469,548
Before we knew it, there wasn’t a living soul left from the Yalu to the DMZ.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[13]:548,689
From a purely intelligence standpoint, it appeared as if the entire country, every man, woman, and child in North Korea, had simply vanished.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[14]:0,86
This mystery only stoked our growing anxiety, given what we had to deal with at home.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[14]:86,143
By now there were outbreaks in Seoul, P’ohang, Taejon.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[14]:143,362
There was the evacuation of Mokpo, the isolation of Kangnung, and, of course, our version of Yonkers at Inchon, and all of it compounded by the need to keep at least half our active divisions along our northern border.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[14]:362,550
Too many in the Ministry of National Defense were convinced that the Pyongyang was just aching for war, waiting eagerly for our darkest moment to come thundering across the 38th Parallel.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[14]:550,609
We in the intelligence community couldn’t disagree more.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[14]:609,720
We kept telling them that if they were waiting for our darkest hour, then that hour had most certainly arrived.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[15]:0,57
Tae Han Min’guk was on the brink of national collapse.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[15]:57,126
Plans were being secretly drafted for a Japanese-style resettlement.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[15]:126,185
Covert teams were already scouting locations in Kamchatka.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[15]:185,303
If the Chang Doctrine hadn’t worked…if just a few more units had broken, if a few more safe zones had collapsed…
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[16]:0,71
Maybe we owe our survival to the North, or at least to the fear of it.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[16]:71,125
My generation never really saw the North as a threat.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[16]:125,243
I’m speaking of the civilians, you understand, those of my age who saw them as a backward, starving, failed nation.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[16]:243,314
My generation had grown up their entire lives in peace and prosperity.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[16]:314,448
The only thing they feared was a German-style reunification that would bring millions of homeless ex-communists looking for a handout.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[17]:0,357
That wasn’t the case with those who came before us…our parents and grandparents…those who lived with the very real specter of invasion hanging over them, the knowledge that at any moment the alarms might sound, the lights might dim, and the bankers, schoolteachers, and taxi drivers might be called to pick up arms and fight to defend their homeland.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[17]:357,469
Their hearts and minds were ever vigilant, and in the end, it was them, not us, who rallied the national spirit.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[18]:0,52
I’m still pushing for an expedition to the North.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[18]:52,87
I’m still blocked at every turn.
