/html/body/div/div[7]/p[21]
KYOTO, JAPAN
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[22]:0,145
[The old photo of Kondo Tatsumi shows a skinny, acne-faced teenager with dull red eyes and bleached blond highlights streaking his unkempt hair.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[22]:145,190
The man I am speaking to has no hair at all.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[22]:190,263
Clean-shaven, tanned and toned, his clear, sharp gaze never leaves mine.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[22]:263,385
Although his manner is cordial and his mood light, this warrior monk retains the composure of a predatory animal at rest.]
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[23]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:0,224
I was an “otaku.” I know that term has come to mean a great many things to a great many people, but for me it simply meant “outsider.” I know Americans, especially young ones, must feel trapped by societal pressure.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:224,239
All humans do.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:239,333
However, if I understand your culture correctly, individualism is something to be encouraged.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:333,425
You revere the “rebel,” the “rogue,” those who stand proudly apart from the masses.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:425,469
For you, individuality is a badge of honor.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:469,502
For us, it is a ribbon of shame.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:502,610
We lived, particularly before the war, in a complex and seemingly infinite labyrinth of external judgments.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:610,770
Your appearance, your speech, everything from the career you held to the way you sneezed had to be planned and orchestrated to follow rigid Confucian doctrine.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:770,843
Some either have the strength, or lack thereof, to accept this doctrine.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:843,895
Others, like myself, chose exile in a better world.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[24]:895,965
That world was cyber space, and it was tailor-made for Japanese otaku.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[25]:0,142
I can’t speak for your educational system, or, indeed, for that of any other country, but ours was based almost entirely on fact retention.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[25]:142,323
From the day we first set foot in a classroom, prewar Japanese children were injected with volumes upon volumes of facts and figures that had no practical application in our lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[25]:323,420
These facts had no moral component, no social context, no human connection to the outside world.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[25]:420,501
They had no reason for existence other than that their mastery allows ascension.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[25]:501,579
Prewar Japanese children were not taught to think, we were taught to memorize.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[26]:0,94
You can understand how this education would easily lend itself to an existence in cyberspace.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[26]:94,245
In a world of information without context, where status was determined on its acquisition and possession, those of my generation could rule like gods.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[26]:245,479
I was a sensei, master over all I surveyed, be it discovering the blood type of the prime minister’s cabinet, or the tax receipts of Matsumoto and Hamada, 1 or the location and condition of all shin-gunto swords of the Pacific War.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[26]:479,592
I didn’t have to worry about my appearance, or my social etiquette, my grades, or my prospects for the future.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[26]:592,637
No one could judge me, no one could hurt me.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[26]:637,700
In this world I was powerful, and more importantly, I was safe!
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:0,151
When the crisis reached Japan, my clique, as with all the others, forgot our previous obsessions and devoted our energies entirely to the living dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:151,257
We studied their physiology, behavior, weaknesses, and the global response to their attack upon humanity.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:257,368
The last subject was my clique’s specialty, the possibility of containment within the Japanese home islands.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:368,440
I collected population statistics, transport networks, police doctrine.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:440,569
I memorized everything from the size of the Japanese merchant fleet, to how many rounds the army’s Type 89 assault rifle held.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:569,603
No fact was too small or obscure.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:603,642
We were on a mission, we barely slept.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:642,750
When school was eventually cancelled, it gave us the ability to be wired in almost twenty-four hours a day.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:750,898
I was the first to hack into Doctor Komatsu’s personal hard drive and read the raw data a full week before he presented his findings to the Diet.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:898,915
This was a coup.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[27]:915,983
It further elevated my status among those who already worshipped me.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[28]
Doctor Komatsu first recommended the evacuation?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:0,8
He did.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:8,55
Like us, he’d been compiling the same facts.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:55,124
But whereas we’d been memorizing them, he’d been analyzing them.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:124,324
Japan was an overcrowded nation: one hundred and twenty-eight million people jammed into less than three hundred and seventy thousand square kilometers of either mountainous or overurbanized islands.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:324,454
Japan’s low crime rate gave it one of the relatively smallest and most lightly armed police forces in the industrialized world.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:454,504
Japan was pretty much also a demilitarized state.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:504,605
Because of American “protection,” our self-defense forces had not seen actual combat since 1945.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:605,790
Even those token troops who were deployed to the Gulf almost never saw any serious action and spent most of their occupation duty within the protected walls of their isolated compound.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:790,895
We had access to all these bits of information, but not the wherewithal to see where they were pointing.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[29]:895,1051
So it took us all by complete surprise when Doctor Komatsu publicly declared that the situation was hopeless and that Japan had to be immediately evacuated.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[30]
That must have been terrifying.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[31]:0,12
Not at all!
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[31]:12,114
It set off an explosion of frenzied activity, a race to discover where our population might resettle.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[31]:114,277
Would it be the South, the coral atolls of the Central and South Pacific, or would we head north, colonizing the Kuriles, Sakhalin, or maybe somewhere in Siberia?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[31]:277,355
Whoever could uncover the answer would be the greatest otaku in cyber history.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[32]
And there was no concern for your personal safety?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:0,15
Of course not.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:15,63
Japan was doomed, but I didn’t live in Japan.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:63,112
I lived in a world of free-floating information.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:112,242
The siafu, 2 that’s what we were calling the infected now, weren’t something to be feared, they were something to be studied.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:242,299
You have no idea the kind of disconnect I was suffering.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:299,393
My culture, my upbringing, and now my otaku lifestyle all combined to completely insulate me.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[33]:393,519
Japan might be evacuated, Japan might be destroyed, and I would watch it all happen from the safety of my digital mountaintop.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[34]
What about your parents?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:0,17
What about them?
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:17,89
We lived in the same apartment, but I never really conversed with them.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:89,129
I’m sure they thought I was studying.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:129,225
Even when school closed I told them I still had to prepare for exams. They never questioned it.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:225,255
My father and I rarely spoke.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:255,355
In the mornings my mother would leave a breakfast tray at my door, at night she would leave dinner.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:355,422
The first time she didn’t leave a tray, I thought nothing of it.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:422,526
I woke up that morning, as I always did; gratified myself, as I always did; logged on, as I always did.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:526,573
It was midday before I started to feel hungry.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:573,645
I hated those feelings, hunger or fatigue or, the worst, sexual desire.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:645,679
Those were physical distractions.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:679,696
They annoyed me.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:696,767
I reluctantly turned away from my computer and opened my bedroom door.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:767,776
No food.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:776,800
I called for my mother.
====
/html/body/div/div[7]/p[35]:800,811
No answer.
====
