/html/body/div/div[15]/p[5]
CIENFUEGOS, CUBA
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[6]:0,60
[Seryosha Garcia Alvarez suggests I meet him at his office.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[6]:60,105
“The view is breathtaking,” he promises.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[6]:105,384
“You will not be disappointed.” On the sixty-ninth floor of the Malpica Savings and Loans building, the second-tallest building in Cuba after Havana’s José Martí Towers, Señor Alvarez’s corner office overlooks both the glittering metropolis and bustling harbor below.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[6]:384,585
It is the “magic hour” for energy-independent buildings like the Malpica, that time of the day when it’s photovoltaic windows capture the setting sun with their almost imperceptible magenta hue.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[6]:585,611
Señor Alvarez was right.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[6]:611,634
I am not disappointed.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[7]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[8]
Cuba won the Zombie War; maybe that’s not the most humble of statements, given what happened to so many other countries, but just look at where we were twenty years ago as opposed to where we are now.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[9]:0,102
Before the war, we lived in a state of quasi-isolation, worse than during the height of the cold war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[9]:102,234
At least in my father’s day you could count on what amounted to economic welfare from the Soviet Union and their ComEcon puppets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[9]:234,327
Since the fall of the communist bloc, though, our existence was one of constant deprivation.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[9]:327,531
Rationed food, rationed fuel…the closest comparison I can make is that of Great Britain during the Blitz, and like that other besieged island, we too lived under the dark cloud of an ever-present enemy.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:0,9
The U.S.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:9,184
blockade, while not as constricting as during the cold war, nonetheless sought to suffocate our economic lifeblood by punishing any nation that attempted free and open trade.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:184,210
As successful as the U.S.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:210,334
strategy was, its most resounding triumph was allowing Fidel to use our northern oppressor as an excuse to remain in power.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:334,385
“You see how hard your life is,” he would say.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:385,574
“The blockade has done this to you, the Yankees have done this to you, and without me, they would be storming our beaches even now!” He was brilliant, Machiavelli’s most favored son.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:574,642
He knew we would never remove him while the enemy was at the gates.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:642,732
And so we endured the hardships and the oppression, the long lines and the hushed voices.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:732,800
This was the Cuba I grew up in, the only Cuba I could ever imagine.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[10]:800,838
That is, until the dead began to rise.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[11]:0,100
Cases were small and immediately contained, mostly Chinese refugees and a few European businessmen.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[11]:100,225
Travel from the United States was still largely prohibited, so we were spared the initial blow of first-wave mass migration.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[11]:225,366
The repressive nature of our fortress society allowed the government to take steps to ensure that the infection was never allowed to spread.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[11]:366,468
All internal travel was suspended, and both the regular army and territorial militias were mobilized.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[11]:468,624
Because Cuba had such a high percentage of doctors per capita, our leader knew the true nature of the infection weeks after the first outbreak was reported.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[12]
By the time of the Great Panic, when the world finally woke up to the nightmare breaking down their doors, Cuba had already prepared itself for war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[13]:0,159
The simple fact of geography spared us the danger of large-scale, overland swarms. Our invaders came from the sea, specifically from an armada of boat people.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[13]:159,325
Not only did they bring the contagion, as we have seen throughout the world, there were also those who believed in ruling their new homes as modern-day conquistadors.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[14]:0,127
Look at what happened in Iceland, a prewar paradise, so safe and secure they never found the need to maintain a standing army.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[14]:127,183
What could they do when the American military withdrew?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[14]:183,259
How could they stop the torrent of refugees from Europe and western Russia?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[14]:259,432
Is it no mystery how that once idyllic arctic haven became a cauldron of frozen blood, and why, to this day, it is still the most heavily infested White Zone on the planet?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[14]:432,561
That could have been us, easily, had it not been for the example set by our brothers in the smaller Windward and Leeward Islands.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[15]:0,120
Those men and women, from Anguilla to Trinidad, can proudly take their place as some of the greatest heroes of the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[15]:120,329
They first eradicated multiple outbreaks along their archipelago, then, with barely a moment to catch their collective breaths, repelled not only seaborne zombies, but an endless flood of human invaders, too.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[15]:329,382
They spilled their blood so that we did not have to.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[15]:382,715
They forced our would-be latifundista to reconsider their plans for conquest, and realize that if a few civilians armed with nothing but small arms and machetes could defend their homelands so tenaciously, what would they find on the shores of a country armed with everything from main battle tanks to radar-guided antiship missiles?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[16]
Naturally, the inhabitants of the Lesser Antilles were not fighting for the best interests of the Cuban people, but their sacrifices did allow us the luxury of setting our own terms. Any seeking sanctuary would find themselves greeted with the saying so common among Norteamericano parents, “While under my roof, you will obey my rules.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[17]:0,213
Not all of the refugees were Yankees; we had our share from mainland Latin America, from Africa, and western Europe, Spain especially—many Spaniards and Canadians had visited Cuba either on business or holiday.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[17]:213,433
I had gotten to know a few of them before the war, nice people, polite, so different from the East Germans of my youth who used to toss handfuls of candy in the air and laugh while we children scrambled for it like rats.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[18]:0,77
The majority of our boat people, however, originated from the United States.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[18]:77,204
Every day more would arrive, by large ship or private craft, even on homemade rafts that brought an ironic smile to our faces.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[18]:204,441
So many of them, a total of five million, equal to almost half of our indigenous population, and along with all the other nationalities, they were placed under the jurisdiction of the government’s “Quarantine Resettlement Program.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[19]:0,72
I would not go so far as to call the Resettlement Centers prison camps.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[19]:72,233
They could not compare to the lives suffered by our political dissidents; the writers and teachers…I had a “friend” who was accused of being a homosexual.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[19]:233,313
His stories from prison cannot compare to even the harshest Resettlement Center.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:0,33
It was not easy living, however.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:33,246
These people, no matter what their prewar occupation or status, were initially put to work as field hands, twelve to fourteen hours a day, growing vegetables in what had once been our state-run sugar plantations.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:246,286
At least the climate was on their side.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:286,342
The temperature was dropping, the skies were darkening.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:342,374
Mother Nature was kind to them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:374,405
The guards, however, were not.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:405,475
“Be glad you’re alive,” they’d shout after each slap or kick.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[20]:475,535
“Keep complaining and we’ll throw you to the zombies!”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[21]:0,335
Every camp had a rumor about the dreaded “zombie pits,” the hole in which they’d throw the “troublemakers.” The DGI [the General Intelligence Directorate] had even planted prisoners in the general population to spread stories about how they personally witnessed men being lowered, headfirst, into the boiling lake of ghouls.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[21]:335,636
This was all just to keep everyone in line, you see, none of it was actually true…though…there were stories about the “Miami whites.” The majority of American Cubanos were welcomed home with open arms. I myself had several relatives living in Daytona who just barely escaped with their lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[21]:636,732
The tears of so many reunions in those early, frantic days could have filled the Caribbean Sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[21]:732,1170
But that first wave of postrevolution immigrants—the affluent elite who had flourished under the old regime and who spent the rest of their lives trying to topple everything we’d worked so hard to build—as far as those aristos were concerned…I am not saying there is any proof that they were thrown to the ghouls by their fat, reactionary, Bacardi blanka drinking asses…But if they were, they can suck Batista’s balls in hell.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[22]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[23]
[A thin, satisfied smile crosses his lips.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[24]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[25]:0,91
Of course, we couldn’t have actually attempted this kind of punishment with your people.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[25]:91,223
Rumors and threats were one thing, but physical action…push a people, any people too far, and you risk the possibility of revolt.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[25]:223,276
Five million Yankees, all rising in open revolution?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[25]:276,289
Unthinkable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[25]:289,408
It already took too many troops to maintain the camps, and that was the initial success of the Yankee invasion of Cuba.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[26]:0,119
We simply didn’t have the manpower to guard five million detainees and almost four thousand kilometers of coastline.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[26]:119,160
We couldn’t fight a war on two fronts.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[26]:160,316
And so the decision was made to dissolve the centers and allow 10 percent of the Yankee detainees to work outside the wire on a specialized parole program.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[26]:316,576
These detainees would do the jobs Cubanos no longer wanted—day laborers, dish washers, and street cleaners—and while their wages would be next to nothing, their labor hours would go to a point system that allowed them to buy the freedom of other detainees.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[27]:0,107
It was an ingenious idea—some Florida Cubano came up with it—and the camps were drained in six months.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[27]:107,200
At first the government tried to keep track of all of them, but that soon proved impossible.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[27]:200,327
Within a year they had almost fully integrated, the “Nortecubanos,” insinuating themselves into every facet of our society.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[28]
Officially the camps had been created to contain the spread of “infection,” but that wasn’t the kind spread by the dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:0,80
You couldn’t see this infection at first, not when we were still under siege.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:80,140
It was still behind closed doors, still spoken in whispers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:140,299
Over the next several years what occurred was not so much a revolution as an evolution, an economic reform here, a legalized, privately owned newspaper there.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:299,352
People began to think more boldly, talk more boldly.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:352,399
Slowly, quietly, the seeds began to take root.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:399,566
I’m sure Fidel would have loved to bring his iron fist crashing down on our fledgling freedoms. Perhaps he might have, if world events had not shifted in our favor.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[29]:566,660
It was when the world governments decided to go on the attack that everything changed forever.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[30]:0,142
Suddenly we became “the Arsenal of Victory.” We were the breadbasket, the manufacturing center, the training ground, and the springboard.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[30]:142,241
We became the air hub for both North and South America, the great dry dock for ten thousand ships.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[30]:241,426
1 We had money, lots of it, money that created an overnight middle class, and a thriving, capitalist economy that needed the refined skills and practical experience of the Nortecubanos.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:0,53
We shared a bond I don’t think can ever be broken.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:53,123
We helped them reclaim their nation, and they helped us reclaim ours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:123,255
They showed us the meaning of democracy…freedom, not just in vague, abstract terms, but on a very real, individually human level.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:255,400
Freedom isn’t just something you have for the sake of having, you have to want something else first and then want the freedom to fight for it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:400,454
That was the lesson we learned from the Nortecubanos.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:454,568
They all had such grand dreams, and they’d lay down their lives for the freedom to make those dreams come true.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[31]:568,619
Why else would El Jefe be so damned afraid of them?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[32]:0,96
I’m not surprised that Fidel knew the tides of freedom were coming to sweep him out of power.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[32]:96,140
I am surprised at how well he rode the wave.
====
