/html/body/div/div[15]/p[41]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[42]:0,67
We were not traitors—I say this before I’ll say anything else.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[42]:67,209
We loved our country, we loved our people, and while we may not have loved those who ruled both, we were unwaveringly loyal to our leadership.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[43]:0,90
We never would have imagined doing what we did had not the situation become so desperate.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[43]:90,172
By the time Captain Chen first voiced his proposal, we were already on the brink.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[43]:172,212
They were in every city, every village.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[43]:212,331
In the nine and a half million square kilometers that made up our country, you couldn’t find one centimeter of peace.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[44]:0,227
The army, arrogant bastards that they were, kept insisting that they had the problem under control, that every day was the turning point and before the next snow fell upon the earth they would have the entire country pacified.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[44]:227,281
Typical army thinking: overaggressive, overconfident.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[44]:281,480
All you need is a group of men, or women, give them matching clothes, a few hours training, something that passes for a weapon, and you have an army, not the best army, but still an army nonetheless.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:0,45
That can’t happen with the navy, any navy.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:45,130
Any ship, no matter how crude, requires considerable energy and materials to create.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:130,208
The army can replace its cannon fodder in hours; for us, it might take years.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:208,276
This tends to make us more pragmatic than our compatriots in green.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:276,397
We tend to look at a situation with a bit more…I don’t want to say caution, but perhaps more strategic conservatism.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:397,444
Withdraw, consolidate, husband your resources.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[45]:444,536
That was the same philosophy as the Redeker Plan, but of course, the army wouldn’t listen.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[46]
They rejected Redeker?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:0,56
Without the slightest consideration or internal debate.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:56,86
How could the army ever lose?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:86,224
With their vast stockpiles of conventional armaments, with their “bottomless well” of manpower…“bottomless well,” unforgivable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:224,293
Do you know why we had such a population explosion during the 1950s?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:293,356
Because Mao believed it was the only way to win a nuclear war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:356,387
This is truth, not propaganda.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:387,559
It was common knowledge that when the atomic dust eventually settled, only a few thousand American or Soviet survivors would be overwhelmed by tens of millions of Chinese.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:559,768
Numbers, that was the philosophy of my grandparents’ generation, and it was the strategy the army was quick to adopt once our experienced, professional troops were devoured in the outbreak’s early stages.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:768,910
Those generals, sick, twisted old criminals sitting safely in their bunker and ordering wave after wave of conscripted teenagers into battle.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:910,977
Did they even think that every dead soldier was now a live zombie?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[47]:977,1222
Did they ever realize that, instead of drowning them in our bottomless well, we were the ones drowning, choking to death as the most populous nation on Earth found itself, for the first time in history, in danger of becoming fatally outnumbered?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[48]:0,49
That was what pushed Captain Chen over the edge.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[48]:49,158
He knew what would happen if the war continued along its course, and what our chances for survival would be.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[48]:158,266
If he thought that there was any hope, he would have grabbed a rifle and hurled himself at the living dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[48]:266,382
He was convinced that soon there would be no more Chinese people, and perhaps, eventually, no more people anywhere.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[48]:382,535
That was why he made his intentions known to his senior officers, declaring that we might be the only chance of preserving something of our civilization.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[49]
Did you agree with his proposal?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:0,37
I didn’t even believe it at first.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:37,80
Escape in our boat, our nuclear submarine?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:80,178
This wasn’t just desertion, slinking out in the middle of a war to save our own pathetic skins.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:178,253
This was stealing one of the motherland’s most valuable national assets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:253,380
The Admiral Zheng He was only one of three ballistic missiles subs and the newest of what the West referred to as the Type 94.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:380,600
She was the child of four parents: Russian assistance, black-market technology, the fruits of anti-American espionage, and, let us not forget, the culmination of nearly five thousand years of continuous Chinese history.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:600,706
She was the most expensive, the most advanced, the most powerful machine our nation had ever constructed.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:706,794
To simply steal her, like a lifeboat from the sinking ship of China, was inconceivable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[50]:794,918
It was only Captain Chen’s force of personality, his deep, fanatical patriotism that convinced me of our only alternative.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[51]
How long did it take to prepare?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:0,14
Three months.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:14,27
It was hell.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:27,85
Qingdao, our home port, was in a constant state of siege.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:85,271
More and more army units were called in to maintain order, and each was just a little less trained, a little less equipped, a little younger, or older, than the one that came before it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:271,368
Some of the surface ship captains had to donate “expendable” crew to shore up base defenses.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:368,417
Our perimeter was under attack almost every day.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:417,491
And through all of this we had to prepare and provision the boat for sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[52]:491,613
It was supposed to be a routinely scheduled patrol; we had to smuggle on board both emergency supplies and family members.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[53]
Family members?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[54]:0,46
Oh yes, that was the cornerstone of the plan.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[54]:46,138
Captain Chen knew the crew wouldn’t leave port unless their families could come with them.
====
