/html/body/div/div[15]/p[78]
So you were alone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[79]:0,11
All alone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[79]:11,78
No home, no friends, no safe harbor no matter how harsh the storm.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[79]:78,153
The Admiral Zheng He was our entire universe: heaven, earth, sun, and moon.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[80]
That must have been very difficult.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:0,70
The first few months passed as though it was merely a regular patrol.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:70,131
Missile subs are designed to hide, and that’s what we did.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:131,148
Deep and silent.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:148,214
We weren’t sure if our own attack subs were out looking for us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:214,267
In all probability our government had other worries.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:267,369
Still, regular battle drills were conducted and the civilians trained in the art of noise discipline.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:369,508
The chief of the boat even rigged special soundproofing for the mess hall so it could be both a schoolroom and play area for the children.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:508,583
The children, especially the younger ones, had no idea what was happening.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:583,696
Many of them had even traveled with their families across infested areas, some barely escaping with their lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:696,784
All they knew was that the monsters were gone, banished to their occasional nightmares.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:784,836
They were safe now, and that’s all that mattered.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:836,892
I guess that is how we all felt those first few months.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:892,939
We were alive, we were together, we were safe.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[81]:939,1015
Given what was happening to the rest of the planet, what more could we want?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[82]
Did you have some way of monitoring the crisis?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:0,17
Not immediately.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:17,127
Our goal was stealth, avoiding both commercial shipping lanes and submarine patrol sectors…ours, and yours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:127,150
We speculated, though.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:150,177
How fast was it spreading?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:177,217
Which countries were the most affected?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:217,254
Was anyone using the nuclear option?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:254,298
If so, that would be the end for all of us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:298,462
In a radiated planet, the walking dead might be the only creatures left “alive.” We weren’t sure what high doses of radiation would do to a zombie’s brain.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:462,553
Would it eventually kill them, riddling their gray matter with multiple, expanding tumors?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:553,712
That would be the case for a regular human brain, but since the living dead contradicted every other law of nature, why should this reaction be any different?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:712,952
Some nights in the wardroom, speaking in low voices over our off-duty tea, we conjured images of zombies as fast as cheetahs, as agile as apes, zombies with mutated brains that grew and throbbed and burst from the confines of their skulls.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:952,1081
Lieutenant Commander Song, our reactor officer, had brought aboard his watercolors and had painted the scene of a city in ruins.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1081,1202
He tried to say that it wasn’t any city in particular but we all recognized the twisted remains of the Pudong skyline.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1202,1233
Song had grown up in Shanghai.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1233,1321
The broken horizon glowed a dull magenta against the pitch-black sky of nuclear winter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1321,1404
A rain of ash peppered the islands of debris that rose from lakes of melted glass.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1404,1681
Snaking through the center of this apocalyptic backdrop was a river, a greenish-brown snake that rose up into a head of a thousand interconnected bodies: cracked skin, exposed brain, flesh dripping from bony arms that reached out from openmouthed faces with red, glowing eyes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1681,1814
I don’t know when Commander Song began his project, only that he secretly unveiled it to a few of us after our third month at sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1814,1860
He never intended to show it to Captain Chen.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1860,1876
He knew better.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[83]:1876,1943
But someone must have talked and the Old Man soon put a stop to it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[84]:0,97
Song was ordered to paint over his work with something cheerful, a summer sunset over Lake Dian.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[84]:97,191
He then followed up with several more “positive” murals on any space of exposed bulkhead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[84]:191,253
Captain Chen also ordered a halt to all off-duty speculation.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[84]:253,393
“Detrimental to the morale of the crew.” I think it pushed him, though, to reestablish some semblance of contact with the outside world.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[85]
Semblance as in active communication, or passive surveillance?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[86]:0,12
The latter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[86]:12,114
He knew Song’s painting and our apocalyptic discussions were the result of our long-term isolation.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[86]:114,216
The only way to quell any further “dangerous thought” was to replace speculation with hard facts.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[86]:216,284
We’d been in total blackout for almost a hundred days and nights.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[86]:284,379
