/html/body/div/div[15]/p[129]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[130]:0,144
We became millionaires, or…at least the barter equivalent: food, medicine, any spare part we needed or the raw materials to manufacture them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[130]:144,264
We got our greenhouse, along with a miniature waste recovery plant to turn our own night soil into valuable fertilizer.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[130]:264,395
We “bought” equipment for a gymnasium, a full wet bar, and home entertainment systems for both the enlisted mess and wardroom.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[130]:395,584
The children were lavished with toys and candy, whatever was left, and most importantly, continuing education from several of the barges that had been converted into international schools.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[130]:584,631
We were welcomed into any home, onto any boat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[130]:631,770
Our enlisted men, and even some of the officers, were given free credit on any one of the five “comfort” boats anchored in the lagoon.
