I wish I could say that we violated orders or physically fought with one another over who should stay.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[179]:512,571
What really happened was much more mundane and reasonable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[179]:571,715
I ordered the scientific team, and any other nonessential personnel, back to Earth, then gave the rest of the crew the choice to remain behind.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[179]:715,883
With the X-38 reentry “lifeboat” gone, we would be technically stranded, but when you think of what was at stake then, I can’t imagine any of us wanting to leave.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[180]:0,61
The ISS is one of the greatest marvels of human engineering.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[180]:61,160
We’re talking about an orbital platform so large it could be seen from Earth with the naked eye.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[180]:160,322
It’d taken sixteen countries over ten years, a couple hundred space walks, and more money than anyone without job security would admit to finally complete her.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[180]:322,398
What would it take to build another one, if another one could ever be built?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[181]:0,129
Even more important than the station was the incalculable, and equally irreplaceable, value of our planet’s satellite network.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[181]:129,361
Back then there were over three thousand in orbit, and humanity depended on them for everything from communications to navigation, from surveillance to something even as mundane yet vital as regular and reliable weather prediction.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[181]:361,488
This network was as important to the modern world as roads had been in ancient times, or rail lines during the industrial age.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[181]:488,584
What would happen to humanity if these all-important links just started dropping out of the sky?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[182]:0,37
Our plan was never to save them all.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[182]:37,75
That was unrealistic and unnecessary.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[182]:75,202
All we had to do was concentrate on the systems most vital to the war effort, just a few dozen birds that had to remain aloft.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[182]:202,243
That alone was worth the risk of staying.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[183]
Were you ever promised a rescue?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:0,31
No, and we didn’t expect it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:31,141
The issue wasn’t how we were going to get back to Earth, it was how we could manage to stay alive up there.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:141,390
Even with all our tanked O2 and emergency perchlorate candles, 2 even with our water recycling system 3 operating at peak capacity, we only had enough food for roughly twenty-seven months, and that was including the test animals in the lab modules.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:390,481
None of them were being used to test any kind of vaccines so their flesh was still edible.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:481,576
I can still hear their little shrieks, still see the spots of blood floating in micro gravity.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:576,624
Even up there, you couldn’t escape the blood.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:624,748
I tried to be scientific about it, calculating the nutritional value of every floating red globule I sucked out of the air.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[184]:748,840
I kept insisting that it was all for the good of the mission and not my own ravenous hunger.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[185]:0,32
Tell me more about the mission.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[185]:32,119
If you were trapped on the station, how did you manage to keep the satellites in orbit?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[186]:0,106
We used the “Jules Verne Three” ATV, 4 the last supply pod launched before French Guyana was overrun.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[186]:106,261
It was originally designed as a one-way vehicle, to be filled with trash after depositing its cargo, then sent back to Earth to burn up in the atmosphere.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[186]:261,329
5 We modified it with manual flight controls and a pilot’s couch.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[186]:329,383
I wish we could have fixed it with a proper viewport.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[186]:383,556
Navigating by video wasn’t fun; neither was having to do my Extra Vehicular Activities, my space walks, in a reentry suit because there wasn’t room for a proper EVA kit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:0,95
Most of my excursions were to the ASTRO, 6 which was basically just a petrol station in space.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:95,204
Satellites, the military, surveillance type, sometimes have to change orbit in order to acquire new targets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:204,306
They do that by firing their maneuvering thrusters and using up their small amount of hydrazine fuel.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:306,474
Before the war, the American military realized it was more cost-effective to have a refueling station already in orbit rather than sending up a lot of manned missions.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:474,504
That’s where ASTRO came in.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:504,665
We modified it to refuel some of the other satellites as well, the civilian models that need just the occasional top-off to boost back up from a decaying orbit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:665,712
It was a marvelous machine: a real time-saver.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:712,750
We had a lot of technology like that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:750,889
There was the “Canadarm,” the fifty-foot robotic inchworm that performed necessary maintenance tasks along the station’s outer skin.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:889,1041
There was “Boba,” the VR-operated robonaut we fitted with a thruster pack so he could work both around the station and away from it on a satellite.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:1041,1152
We also had a little squadron of PSAs, 7 these free-floating robots, about the shape and size of a grapefruit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:1152,1222
All of this wondrous technology was designed to make our jobs easier.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[187]:1222,1258
I wish they hadn’t worked so well.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[188]:0,75
We had maybe an hour a day, maybe even two, where there was nothing to do.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[188]:75,253
You could sleep, you could exercise, you could reread the same books, you could listen to Radio Free Earth or to the music we’d brought with us (over and over and over again).
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[188]:253,423
I don’t know how many times I listened to that Redgum song: “God help me, I was only nineteen.” It was my father’s favorite, reminded him of his time in Vietnam.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[188]:423,506
I prayed that all that army training was helping to keep him and my mum alive now.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[188]:506,611
I hadn’t heard anything from him, or anyone else in Oz since the government had relocated to Tasmania.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[188]:611,778
I wanted to believe they were all right, but watching what was happening on Earth, as most of us did during our off-duty hours, made it almost impossible to have hope.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[189]:0,115
They say that during the cold war, American spy birds could read the copy of Pravda in a Soviet citizen’s hands.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[189]:115,157
I’m not sure if that’s entirely true.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[189]:157,219
I don’t know the tech specs of that generation of hardware.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[189]:219,357
But I can tell you that these modern ones whose signals we pirated from their relay birds—these could show muscles tear and bones snap.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[189]:357,482
You could read the lips of victims crying out for mercy, or the color of their eyes when they bulged with their last breath.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[189]:482,616
You could see at what point red blood began to turn brown, and how it looked on gray London cement as opposed to white, Cape Cod sand.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:0,60
We had no control over what the spy birds chose to observe.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:60,102
Their targets were determined by the U.S.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:102,112
military.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:112,317
We saw a lot of battles—Chongqing, Yonkers; we watched a company of Indian troops try to rescue civilians trapped in Ambedkar Stadium in Delhi, then become trapped themselves and retreat to Gandhi Park.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:317,414
I watched their commander form his men into a square, the kind the Limeys used in colonial days.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:414,454
It worked, at least for a little while.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:454,553
That was the only frustrating part about satellite surveillance; you could only watch, not listen.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:553,670
We didn’t know that the Indians were running out of ammunition, only that the Zed Heads were starting to close in.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:670,758
We saw a helo hover overhead and watched as the commander argued with his subordinates.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:758,835
We didn’t know it was General Raj-Singh, we didn’t even know who he was.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:835,941
Don’t listen to what the critics say about that man, about how he buggered off when things got too hot.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:941,956
We saw it all.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:956,1053
He did try to put up a fight, and one of his blokes did smash him in the face with a rifle butt.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:1053,1117
He was out cold when they hauled him into that waiting chopper.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[190]:1117,1197
It was a horrible feeling, seeing it all so close and yet unable to do anything.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[191]:0,112
We had our own observation gear, both the civilian research birds and the equipment right there on the station.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[191]:112,230
The images they gave us weren’t half as powerful as the military versions, but they were still frighteningly clear.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[191]:230,326
They gave us our first look at the mega swarms over central Asia and the American Great Plains.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[191]:326,412
Those were truly massive, miles across, like the American buffalo must have once been.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[192]:0,80
We watched the evacuation of Japan and couldn’t help but marvel at the scale.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[192]:80,125
Hundreds of ships, thousands of small boats.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[192]:125,280
We lost count of how many helicopters buzzed back and forth from the rooftops to the armada, or how many jetliners made their final run north to Kamchatka.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:0,124
We were the first ones to discover zombie holes, the pits that the undead dig when they’re going after burrowing animals.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:124,309
At first we thought they were just isolated incidents until we noticed that they were spreading all over the world; sometimes more than one would appear in close proximity to the next.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:309,478
There was a field in southern England—I guess there must have been a high concentration of rabbits—that was just riddled with holes, all different depths and sizes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:478,527
Many of them had large, dark stains around them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:527,606
Although we couldn’t zoom in close enough, we were pretty sure it was blood.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:606,674
For me that was the most terrifying example of our enemy’s drive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:674,743
They displayed no conscious thought, just sheer biological instinct.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:743,834
I once watched a Zed Head go after something, probably a golden mole, in the Namib Desert.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:834,885
The mole had burrowed deep in the slope of a dune.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:885,969
As the ghoul tried to go after it, the sand kept pouring down and filling the hole.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:969,1041
The ghoul didn’t stop, didn’t react in any way, it just kept going.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:1041,1230
I watched it for five days, the fuzzy image of this G digging, and digging, and digging, then suddenly one morning just stopping, getting up, and shuffling away as if nothing had happened.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:1230,1259
It must have lost the scent.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[193]:1259,1276
Good on the mole.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:0,81
For all our enhanced optics, nothing had quite the same impact as the naked eye.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:81,154
To just look through the view port down on our fragile little biosphere.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:154,294
To see the massive ecological devastation makes one understand how the modern environmental movement began with the American space program.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:294,621
There were so many fires, and I don’t just mean the buildings, or the forests, or even the oil rigs blazing out of control—bleeding Saudis actually went ahead and did it 8 —I mean the campfires as well, what had to be at least a billion of them, tiny orange specks covering the Earth where electric lights had once been.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:621,690
Every day, every night, it seemed like the whole planet was burning.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:690,945
We couldn’t even begin to calculate the ash count but we guesstimated it was equivalent to a low-grade nuclear exchange between the United States and former Soviet Union, and that’s not including the actual nuclear exchange between Iran and Pakistan.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:945,1039
We watched and recorded those as well, the flashes and fires that gave me eye spots for days.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[194]:1039,1129
Nuclear autumn was already beginning to set in, the gray-brown shroud thickening each day.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[195]:0,96
It was like looking down on an alien planet, or on Earth during the last great mass extinction.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[195]:96,204
Eventually conventional optics became useless in the shroud, leaving us with only thermal or radar sensors.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[195]:204,275
Earth’s natural face vanished behind a caricature of primary colors.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[195]:275,399
It was through one of these systems, the Aster sensor aboard the Terra Satellite, that we saw the Three Gorges Dam collapse.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[196]:0,132
Roughly ten trillion gallons of water, carrying debris, silt, rocks, trees, cars, houses, and house-sized pieces of the dam itself!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[196]:132,201
It was alive, a brown and white dragon racing to the East China Sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[196]:201,359
When I think of the people in its path…trapped in barricaded buildings, unable to escape the tidal wave because of the Zed Heads right outside their doors.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[196]:359,405
No one knows how many people died that night.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[196]:405,448
Even today, they’re still finding bodies.
