====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[200]:0,146
When I think about how the Chinese leadership tried to explain it all away…Have you ever read a transcript of the Chinese president’s speech?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[200]:146,224
We actually watched the broadcast from a pirated signal off their Sinosat II.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[200]:224,274
He called it an “unforeseen tragedy.” Really?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[200]:274,286
Unforeseen?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[200]:286,357
Was it unforeseen that the dam had been built on an active fault line?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[200]:357,556
Was it unforeseen that the increased weight of a giant reservoir had induced earthquakes in the past 9 and that cracks had already been detected in the foundation months before the dam was completed?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:0,53
He called it an “unavoidable accident.” Bastard.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:53,228
They had enough troops to wage open warfare in almost every major city, but they couldn’t spare a couple of traffic cops to protect against a catastrophe waiting to happen?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:228,352
No one could imagine the repercussions of abandoning both the seismic warning stations and the emergency spillway controls?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:352,581
And then to try to change their story halfway through, to say that they’d actually done everything they could to protect the dam, that, at the time of the disaster, valiant troops of the PLA had given their lives to defend it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:581,757
Well, I’d been personally observing Three Gorges for over a year leading up to the disaster and the only PLA soldiers I ever saw had given their lives a long, long time ago.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:757,824
Did they really expect their own people to buy such a blatant lie?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[201]:824,884
Did they really expect anything less than all-out rebellion?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[202]:0,127
Two weeks after the start of the revolution, we received our first and only signal from the Chinese space station, Yang Liwei.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[202]:127,240
It was the only other manned facility in orbit, but couldn’t compare to such an exquisite masterpiece as ours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[202]:240,379
It was more of a slapdash job, Shenzhou modules and Long March fuel tanks cobbled together like a giant version of the old American Skylab.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[203]:0,47
We’d been trying to contact them for months.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[203]:47,91
We weren’t even sure if there was a crew.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[203]:91,246
All we got was a recorded message in perfect Hong Kong English to keep our distance lest we invite a response of “deadly force.” What an insane waste!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[203]:246,315
We could have worked together, traded supplies, technical expertise.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[203]:315,434
Who knows what we could have accomplished if we had only chucked the politics and come together as human bloody beings.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[204]:0,126
We’d convinced ourselves that the station had never been inhabited at all, that their deadly force warning was just a ruse.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[204]:126,206
We couldn’t have been more surprised when the signal came over our ham radio.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[204]:206,297
10 It was a live human voice, tired, frightened, and cutting out after only a few seconds.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[204]:297,362
It was all I needed to board the Verne and head over to the Yang.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:0,87
As soon as it came over the horizon I could tell that its orbit had shifted radically.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:87,130
As I closed the distance, I could see why.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:130,273
Their escape pod had blown its hatch, and because it was still docked to the primary airlock, the entire station had depressurized in seconds.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:273,321
As a precaution, I requested docking clearance.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:321,336
I got nothing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:336,504
As I came aboard, I could see that even though the station was clearly large enough for a crew of seven or eight, it only had the bunk space and personal kits for two.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:504,613
I found the Yang packed with emergency supplies, enough food, water, and O2 candles for at least five years.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:613,660
What I couldn’t figure out at first was why.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:660,736
There was no scientific equipment aboard, no intelligence-gathering assets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:736,848
It was almost like the Chinese government had sent these two men into space for no other purpose than to exist.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:848,932
Fifteen minutes into my floatabout, I found the first of several scuttling charges.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:932,1004
This space station was little more than a giant Orbital Denial Vehicle.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:1004,1227
If those charges were to detonate, the debris from a four-hundred-metric-ton space station would not only be enough to damage or destroy any other orbiting platform, but any future space launch would be grounded for years.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[205]:1227,1318
It was a “Scorched Space” policy, “if we can’t have it, neither can anyone else.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:0,52
All the station’s systems were still operational.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:52,171
There had been no fire, no structural damage, no reason I could see to cause the accident of the escape pod’s hatch.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:171,259
I found the body of a lone taikonaut with his hand still clinging to the hatch release.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:259,363
He was wearing one of their pressurized escape suits, but the faceplate had been shattered by a bullet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:363,416
I’m guessing the shooter was blown out into space.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:416,587
I’d like to believe that the Chinese revolution wasn’t just restricted to Earth, that the man who’d blown the hatch was also the one who had attempted to signal us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:587,630
His mate must have stuck by the old guard.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:630,703
Maybe Mister Loyalist had been ordered to set off the scuttling charges.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:703,837
Zhai—that was the name on his personal effects—Zhai had tried to blast his mate into space and had caught a round in the process.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:837,869
Makes for a good tale, I think.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[206]:869,909
That’s how I’m going to remember it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[207]:0,52
Is that how you were able to extend your endurance?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[207]:52,90
By using the supplies aboard the Yang?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:0,86
[He gives me a thumbs-up.] We cannibalized every inch of it for spares and materials.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:86,216
We would have liked to have merged the two platforms together but we didn’t have the tools or manpower for such an undertaking.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:216,277
We might been able to use the escape pod to return to Earth.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:277,318
It had a heat shield and room for three.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:318,340
It was very tempting.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:340,469
But the station’s orbit was decaying rapidly, and we had to make a choice then and there, escape to Earth or resupply the ISS.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[208]:469,499
You know which choice we made.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[209]:0,66
Before we finally abandoned her, we laid our friend Zhai to rest.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[209]:66,229
We strapped his body into its bunk, brought his personal kit back to the ISS, and said a few words in his honor as the Yang burned up in the Earth’s atmosphere.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[209]:229,347
For all we knew he might have been the loyalist, not the rebel, but either way, his actions allowed us to stay alive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[209]:347,470
Three more years we remained in orbit, three more years that wouldn’t have been possible without the Chinese consumables.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[210]:0,137
I still think it’s one of the war’s great ironies that our replacement crew ended up arriving in a privately owned civilian vehicle.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[210]:137,212
Spacecraft Three, the ship originally designed for prewar orbital tourism.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[210]:212,275
The pilot, with his cowboy hat and big, confident Yankee grin.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[210]:275,387
[He tries his best Texas accent.] “Anyone order takeout?” [He laughs, then winces and self-medicates again.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:0,67
Sometimes I’m asked if we regretted our decision to stay aboard.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:67,97
I can’t speak for my mates.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:97,162
On their deathbeds they both said they’d do it all over again.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:162,182
How can I disagree?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:182,333
I don’t regret the physical therapy that followed, getting to know my bones again and remembering why the good Lord gave us legs in the first place.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:333,473
I don’t regret being exposed to so much cosmic radiation, all those unprotected EVAs, all that time with inadequate shielding in the ISS.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:473,496
I don’t regret this.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:496,645
[He motions to the hospital room and machinery attached to his body.] We made our choice, and, I’d like to think, we made a difference in the end.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[211]:645,692
Not bad for the son of an Andamooka opal miner.
