/html/body/div/div[15]/p[249]
[He turns to another screen on the far wall, nodding to an operator, and the image dissolves into a wartime map of the continental United States.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[250]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[251]:0,32
Two hundred million zombies 1 .
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[251]:32,97
Who can even visualize that type of number, let alone combat it?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[251]:97,394
At least this time around we knew what we were combating, but when you added up all the experience, all the data we’d compiled on their origin, their physiology, their strengths, their weaknesses, their motives, and their mentality, it still presented us with a very gloomy prospect for victory.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[252]:0,119
The book of war, the one we’ve been writing since one ape slapped another, was completely useless in this situation.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[252]:119,158
We had to write a new one from scratch.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[253]:0,132
All armies, be they mechanized or mountain guerilla, have to abide by three basic restrictions: they have to be bred, fed, and led.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[253]:132,475
Bred: you need warm bodies, or else you don’t have an army; fed: once you’ve got that army, they’ve got to be supplied; and led: no matter how decentralized that fighting force is, there has to be someone among them with the authority to say “follow me.” Bred, fed, and led; and none of these restrictions applied to the living dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:0,50
Did you ever read All Quiet on the Western Front?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:50,197
Remarque paints a vivid picture of Germany becoming “empty,” meaning that toward the end of the war, they were simply running out of soldiers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:197,383
You can fudge the numbers, send the old men and little boys, but eventually you’re going to hit the ceiling…unless every time you killed an enemy, he came back to life on your side.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:383,448
That’s how Zack operated, swelling his ranks by thinning ours!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:448,476
And it only worked one way.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:476,513
Infect a human, he becomes a zombie.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:513,549
Kill a zombie, he becomes a corpse.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[254]:549,614
We could only get weaker, while they might actually get stronger.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[255]:0,52
All human armies need supplies, this army didn’t.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[255]:52,122
No food, no ammo, no fuel, not even water to drink or air to breathe!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[255]:122,184
There were no logistics lines to sever, no depots to destroy.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[255]:184,361
You couldn’t just surround and starve them out, or let them “wither on the vine.” Lock a hundred of them in a room and three years later they’ll come out just as deadly.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[256]:0,138
It’s ironic that the only way to kill a zombie is to destroy its brain, because, as a group, they have no collective brain to speak of.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[256]:138,230
There was no leadership, no chain of command, no communication or cooperation on any level.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[256]:230,304
There was no president to assassinate, no HQ bunker to surgically strike.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[256]:304,431
Each zombie is its own, self-contained, automated unit, and this last advantage is what truly encapsulates the entire conflict.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:0,94
You’ve heard the expression “total war”; it’s pretty common throughout human history.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:94,328
Every generation or so, some gasbag likes to spout about how his people have declared “total war” against an enemy, meaning that every man, woman, and child within his nation was committing every second of their lives to victory.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:328,366
That is bullshit on two basic levels.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:366,475
First of all, no country or group is ever 100 percent committed to war; it’s just not physically possible.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:475,591
You can have a high percentage, so many people working so hard for so long, but all of the people, all of the time?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:591,651
What about the malingerers, or the conscientious objectors?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:651,715
What about the sick, the injured, the very old, the very young?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:715,793
What about when you’re sleeping, eating, taking a shower, or taking a dump?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:793,827
Is that a “dump for victory”?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:827,889
That’s the first reason total war is impossible for humans.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:889,939
The second is that all nations have their limits.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:939,1197
There might be individuals within that group who are willing to sacrifice their lives; it might even be a relatively high number for the population, but that population as a whole will eventually reach its maximum emotional and physiological breaking point.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:1197,1265
The Japanese reached theirs with a couple of American atomic bombs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:1265,1408
The Vietnamese might have reached theirs if we’d dropped a couple more, 2 but, thank all holy Christ, our will broke before it came to that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[257]:1408,1626
That is the nature of human warfare, two sides trying to push the other past its limit of endurance, and no matter how much we like to talk about total war, that limit is always there…unless you’re the living dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[258]:0,85
For the first time in history, we faced an enemy that was actively waging total war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[258]:85,118
They had no limits of endurance.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[258]:118,163
They would never negotiate, never surrender.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[258]:163,316
They would fight until the very end because, unlike us, every single one of them, every second of every day, was devoted to consuming all life on Earth.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[258]:316,387
That’s the kind of enemy that was waiting for us beyond the Rockies.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[258]:387,428
That’s the kind of war we had to fight.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[259]
DENVER, COLORADO, USA
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[260]:0,46
[We have just finished dinner at the Wainios.
====
