/html/body/div/div[15]/p[261]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:0,63
It was kinda like stepping back in time, the new army, I mean.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:63,167
It couldn’t have been any more different from the one I’d fought, and almost died with, at Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:167,267
We weren’t mechanized anymore—no tanks, no arty, no tread jobs 1 at all, not even the Bradleys.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:267,357
Those were still in reserve, being modified for when we’d have to take back the cities.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:357,473
No, the only wheeled vehicles we had, the Humvees and a few M-trip-Seven ASVs, 2 were used to carry ammo and stuff.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:473,556
We hoofed it, all the way, marching in column like you see in Civil War paintings.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:556,696
There was a lot of references to “the Blue” versus “the Gray,” mainly because of Zack’s skin color and the shade of our new BDUs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:696,777
They didn’t bother with camo schemes anymore; in any case, what was the point?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:777,842
And, I guess, navy blue was the cheapest dye they had back then.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:842,900
The BDU itself looked more like a SWAT team’s coverall.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:900,1002
It was light and comfortable and interwoven with Kevlar, I think it was Kevlar, 3 bite-proof threads.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:1002,1075
It had the option of gloves and a hood that would cover your whole face.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[262]:1075,1138
Later, in urban hand-to-hand, that option saved a lot of lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:0,46
Everything had kind of a retro feel about it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:46,121
Our Lobos looked like something out of, I don’t know, Lord of the Rings?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:121,216
Standard orders were to use it only when necessary, but, trust me, we made it necessary a lot.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:216,284
It just felt good, you know, swingin’ that solid hunk a’ steel.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:284,317
It made it personal, empowering.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:317,349
You could feel the skull split.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:349,409
A real rush, like you were taking back your life, you know?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[263]:409,447
Not that I minded pulling the trigger.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:0,57
Our primary weapon was the SIR, standard infantry rifle.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:57,173
The wood furniture made it look like a World War II gun; I guess composite materials were too hard to mass-produce.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:173,224
I’m not sure where the SIR supposedly came from.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:224,264
I’ve heard it was a modcop of the AK.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:264,399
I’ve also heard that it was a stripped-down version of the XM 8, which the army was already planning as its next-gen assault weapon.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:399,545
I’ve even heard that it was invented, tested, and first produced during the siege of the Hero City, and the plans were transmitted to Honolulu.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:545,594
Honestly, I don’t know, and I so don’t care.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:594,701
It might have kicked hard, and it only fired on semi, but it was super accurate and it never, ever jammed!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:701,820
You could drag it through the mud, leave it in the sand, you could drop it in saltwater and let it sit there for days.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:820,890
No matter what you did to this baby, it just wouldn’t let you down.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:890,1018
The only bells and whistles it had was a conversion kit of extra parts, furniture, and additional barrels of different lengths.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:1018,1158
You could go long-range sniper, midrange rifle, or close-combat carbine, all in the same hour, and without reaching farther than your ruck.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:1158,1289
It also had a spike, this little flip-out job, about eight inches long, that you could use in a pinch if your Lobo wasn’t handy.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:1289,1389
We used to joke “careful, you’ll poke somebody’s eye out,” which, of course, we did plenty.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[264]:1389,1593
The SIR made a pretty good close combat weapon, even without the spike, and when you add all the other things that made it so awesome, you can see why we always referred to it, respectfully, as “Sir.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[265]:0,104
Our staple ammo was the NATO 5.56 “Cherry PIE.” PIE stands for pyrotechnically initiated explosive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[265]:104,124
Outstanding design.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[265]:124,205
It would shatter on entry into Zack’s skull and fragments would fry its brain.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[265]:205,283
No risk of spreading infected gray matter, and no need for wasteful bonfires.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[265]:283,353
On BS 4 duty, you didn’t even have to decap before you buried them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[265]:353,400
Just dig the trench and roll the whole body in.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:0,62
Yeah, it was a new army, as much the people as anything else.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:62,141
Recruitment had changed, and being a grunt meant something very different now.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:141,371
You still had the old requirements—physical stamina, mental competence, the motivation and discipline to master difficult challenges in extreme conditions—but all that was mouse farts if you couldn’t hack long-term Z-shock.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:371,430
I saw a lot of good friends just lose it under the strain.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:430,518
Some of them collapsed, some turned their weapons on themselves, some on their buddies.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:518,590
It didn’t have anything to do with being brave or anything like that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:590,844
I once read this British SAS survival guide that talked all about the “warrior” personality, how your family’s supposed to be emotionally and financially stable, and how you’re not even supposed to be attracted to girls when you’re real young.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[266]:844,916
[Grunts.] Survival guides…[Jerks his hand in a masturbatory movement.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:0,147
But the new faces, they could have been from anywhere: your neighbor, your aunt, that geeky substitute teacher, or that fat, lazy slob at the DMV.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:147,264
From former insurance salesmen to a guy who I’m damn sure was Michael Stipe, although I never got him to admit it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:264,371
I guess it all made sense; anyone who couldn’t roll wouldn’t have made it this far in the first place.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:371,417
Everyone was already a veteran in some sense.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:417,510
My battle buddy, Sister Montoya, fifty-two years old, she’d been a nun, still was I guess.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:510,646
Five three and a buck even, she’d protected her whole Sunday school class for nine days with nothing but a six-foot iron candlestick.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[267]:646,830
I don’t know how she managed to hump that ruck, but she did, without complaining, from our assembly area in Needles, all the way to our contact site just outside of Hope, New Mexico.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[268]:0,6
Hope.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[268]:6,58
I’m not kidding, the town was actually named Hope.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[269]:0,119
They say the brass chose it because of the terrain, clear and open with the desert in front and the mountains in back.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[269]:119,211
Perfect, they said, for an opening engagement, and that the name had nothing to do with it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[269]:211,217
Right.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[270]:0,53
The brass really wanted this test-op to go smoothly.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[270]:53,126
It’d be the first major ground engagement we’d fought since Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[270]:126,211
It was that moment, you know, like, when a lot of different things all come together.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[271]
Watershed?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[272]:0,15
Yeah, I think.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[272]:15,162
All the new people, the new stuff, the new training, the new plan—everything was supposed to sort of mix together for this one first big kickoff.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[273]:0,47
We’d encountered a couple dozen Gs en route.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[273]:47,129
Sniffer dogs would find them, and handlers with silenced weapons would drop them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[273]:129,184
We didn’t want to attract too many till we were set.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[273]:184,218
We wanted this to be on our terms.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[274]:0,104
We started planting our “garden”: shelter stakes with orange Day-Glo tape in rows every ten meters.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[274]:104,178
They were our range markers, showing us exactly where to zero our sights.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[274]:178,277
For some of us there was also some light duty like clearing the brush or arranging the ammo crates.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[275]:0,161
For the rest of us, there was nothing to do except wait, just grab some chow, recharge our camel packs, or even snag some bag time, if it was possible to sleep.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[275]:161,197
We’d learned a lot since Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[275]:197,225
The brass wanted us rested.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[275]:225,280
The problem was, it gave us all too much time to think.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:0,53
Did you see the movie, the one Elliot made about us?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:53,213
That scene with the campfire and the grunts all jawing in this witty dialogue, the stories and the dreams for the future, and even that guy with the harmonica.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:213,244
Dude, it was so not like that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:244,368
First of all, it was the middle of the day, no campfires, no harmonica under the stars, and also everyone was really quiet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:368,531
You knew what everyone was thinking though, “What the hell are we doing here?” This was Zack’s house now, and as far as we were concerned, he could have it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:531,728
We’d all had plenty of pep talks about “The Future of the Human Spirit.” We’d seen the president’s speech God knows how many times, but the prez wasn’t out here on Zack’s front lawn.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:728,774
We had a good thing going behind the Rockies.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[276]:774,811
What the hell were we doing out here?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[277]:0,100
Around 1300 hours, the radios started squawking, it was the K-handlers whose dogs had made contact.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[277]:100,159
We locked and loaded and took our place on the firing line.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[278]:0,100
That was the centerpiece of our whole new battle doctrine, back into the past like everything else.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[278]:100,166
We massed in a straight line, two ranks: one active, one reserve.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[278]:166,286
The reserve was so when anyone in the front rank needed a weapon recharge, their fire wouldn’t be missed on the line.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[278]:286,399
Theoretically, with everyone either firing or reloading, we could keep Zack falling as long as the ammo held out.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[279]:0,57
We could hear the barking, the Ks were bringing them in.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[279]:57,104
We started seeing Gs on the horizon, hundreds.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[279]:104,199
I started shaking even though it wasn’t the first time I’d had to face Zack since Yonkers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[279]:199,251
I’d been in the clean and sweep operations in LA.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[279]:251,320
I’d done my time in the Rockies when the summer thawed the passes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[279]:320,349
Each time I got major shakes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:0,49
The dogs were recalled, racing behind our lines.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:49,103
We switched over to our Primary Enticement Mechanism.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:103,130
Every army had one by now.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:130,288
The Brits would use bagpipes, the Chinese used bugles, the Sou’fricans used to smack their rifles with their assegais 5 and belt out these Zulu war chants.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:288,326
For us, it was hard-core Iron Maiden.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:326,374
Now, personally, I’ve never been a metal fan.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:374,474
Straight classic rock’s my thing, and Hendrix’s “Driving South” is about as heavy as I get.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:474,585
But I had to admit, standing there in that desert wind, with “The Trooper” thumping in my chest, I got it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:585,631
The PEM wasn’t really for Zack’s benefit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:631,740
It was to psych us up, take away some of Zack’s mojo, you know, “take the piss out,” as the Brits say.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:740,904
Right about the time Dickinson was belting “As you plunge into a certain death” I was pumped, SIR charged and ready, eyes fixed on this growing, closing horde.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[280]:904,964
I was, like, “C’mon, Zack, let’s fuckin’ do this!”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[281]:0,74
Just before they reached the front range marker, the music began to fade.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[281]:74,152
The squad leaders shouted, “Front rank, ready!” and the first line knelt.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[281]:152,274
Then came the order to “take aim!” and then, as we all held our breath, as the music clicked off, we heard “FIRE!”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:0,115
The front rank just rippled, cracking like a SAW on full auto and dropping every G that crossed the first markers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:115,170
We had strict orders, only the ones crossing the line.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:170,191
Wait for the others.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:191,227
We’d trained this way for months.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:227,256
By now it was pure instinct.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:256,334
Sister Montoya raised her weapon above her head, the signal for an empty mag.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:334,411
We switched positions, I flipped off my safety, and sighted my first target.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:411,479
She was a noob, 6 couldn’t have been dead more than a year or so.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:479,547
Her dirty blond hair hung in patches from her tight, leathery skin.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:547,630
Her swollen belly puffed through a faded black T-shirt that read G IS FOR GANGSTA.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:630,868
I centered my sight between her shrunken, milky blue eyes…you know it’s not really the eyes that make them look all cloudy, it’s actually tiny dust scratches on the surface, thousands of them, because Zack doesn’t make any tears.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:868,950
Those scratched-up baby blues were looking right at me when I pulled the trigger.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:950,1029
The round knocked her on her back, steam coming from the hole in her forehead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[282]:1029,1105
I took a breath, sighted my next target, and that was that, I was locked in.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[283]:0,47
Doctrine calls for one shot every full second.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[283]:47,77
Slow, steady, mechanical-like.
====
