/html/body/div/div[15]/p[290]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[291]
Shooting, switching, reloading, grabbing sips from your camel pack, grabbing clips from the “Sandlers.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[292]
Sandlers?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[293]:0,101
Yeah, the Recharge Teams, this special reserve unit that did nothing but make sure we never ran dry.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[293]:101,213
You only had a certain number of clips on you and it would take a lot more time to reload each individual clip.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[293]:213,359
The Sandlers ran up and down the line collecting empty clips, recharging them from crated ammo, and then passing them out to anyone who signaled.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[293]:359,603
The story is that when the army started training with RTs, one of the guys started doin’ an Adam Sandler impression, you know, “Water Boy”—“Ammo Boy.” The officers weren’t too jazzed with the tag, but the Recharge Teams loved it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[293]:603,662
Sandlers were lifesavers, drilled like a fuckin’ ballet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[293]:662,741
I don’t think anyone that day or night ever found themselves one round short.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[294]
That night?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[295]
They just kept coming, full on Chain Swarm.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[296]
That’s a large-scale attack?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[297]:0,16
More than that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[297]:16,60
One G sees you, comes after you, and moans.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[297]:60,187
A click away, another G hears that moan, comes after it, and moans himself, then another one another click away, then another.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[297]:187,295
Dude, if the area’s thick enough, if the chain’s unbroken, who knows how far you can pull them in from.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[297]:295,346
And we’re just talking one after the other here.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[297]:346,389
Try ten every click, a hundred, a thousand.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[298]:0,146
They started piling up, forming this artificial palisade at the first range marker, this ridge of corpses that got higher and higher each minute.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[298]:146,286
We were actually building an undead fortification, creating a situation where all we had to do was pop every head that popped over the top.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[298]:286,318
The brass had planned for this.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[298]:318,397
They had a periscope tower thingy 7 that let officers see right over the wall.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[298]:397,525
They also had real-time downlinks from satellites and recon drones, although we, the grunts, had no idea what they were seeing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[298]:525,625
Land Warrior was gone for now so all we had to do was concentrate on what was in front of our faces.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[299]:0,128
We started getting contacts from all sides, either coming around the wall or else being drawn in from our flanks and even rear.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[299]:128,195
Again, the brass was waiting for this and ordered us to form an RS.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[300]
A Reinforced Square.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:0,63
Or a “Raj-Singh,” I guess after the guy who reinvented it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:63,151
We formed a tight square, still two ranks, with our vehicles and whatnot in the center.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:151,206
That was a dangerous gamble, cutting us off like that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:206,294
I mean, yeah, it didn’t work that first time in India only ’cause the ammo ran out.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:294,355
But there was no guarantee it wouldn’t happen again to us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:355,468
What if the brass had goofed, hadn’t packed enough rounds or underestimated how strong Zack would be that day?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[301]:468,569
It could have been Yonkers all over again; worse, because no one would be getting out of there alive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[302]
But you did have enough ammunition.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:0,18
More than enough.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:18,59
The vehicles were packed to their roofs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:59,94
We had water, we had replacements.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:94,222
If you needed a fiver, you just raised your weapon and one of the Sandlers would jump in and take our place on the firing line.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:222,301
You’d grab a bite of I-Rations, 8 soak your face, stretch, drain the weasel.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:301,433
No one would ever volunteer for a fiver, but they had these KO 9 teams, combat shrinks who were observing everyone’s performance.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:433,618
They’d been with us since our early days on the range, knew us each by name and face, and knew, don’t ask me how, when the stress of battle was starting to degrade our performance.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:618,658
We didn’t know, I certainly didn’t.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:658,749
There were a couple times I’d miss a shot or maybe take a half second instead of a full.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:749,834
Then suddenly I’d get this tap on my shoulder and I knew I was out of it for five.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:834,852
It really worked.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:852,960
Before I knew it, I was back on the line, bladder empty, stomach quiet, a few less kinks and muscle cramps.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[303]:960,1117
It made a world of difference, and anyone who thinks we could have lasted without it should try hitting a moving bull’s-eye every second for fifteen hours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[304]
What about at night?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[305]:0,111
We used searchlights from the vehicles, powerful, red-coated beams so it didn’t mess with your night vision.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[305]:111,246
The only creepy thing about night fighting, other than the redness from the lights, is the glow a round makes when it enters the head.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[305]:246,403
That’s why we called them “Cherry PIES,” because if the bullet’s chemcomp wasn’t mixed right, it would burn so bright it made their eyes glow red.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[305]:403,539
That was a cure for constipation, especially later on, on nights when you pulled guard duty, and one would come at you out of the dark.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[305]:539,606
Those glowing red eyes, frozen in time the second before it falls.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[305]:606,616
[Shivers.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[306]
How did you know the battle was over?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:0,26
When we stopped shooting?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:26,75
[Laughs.] No, that’s actually a good question.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:75,130
Around, I don’t know, 0400, it started to taper off.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:130,166
Heads weren’t poking out as much.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:166,191
The moan was dying down.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:191,332
The officers didn’t tell us that the attack was almost over, but you could see them looking through their scopes, talking on their radios.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:332,373
You could see the relief in their faces.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:373,423
I think the last shot was fired just before dawn.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[307]:423,466
After that, we just waited for first light.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[308]:0,74
It was kinda eerie, the sun rising over this mountainous ring of corpses.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[308]:74,178
We were totally walled in, all sides were piled at least twenty feet high and over a hundred feet deep.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[308]:178,273
I’m not sure how many we killed that day, stats always vary depending on who you get it from.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[309]:0,91
The dozer-blade Humvees had to push a path through the corpse ring just to let us get out.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[309]:91,257
There were still living Gs, some slow ones who were late to the party or who had tried to climb up and over their dead friends and had slid back down into the mound.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[309]:257,316
When we started burying the bodies they came tumbling out.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[309]:316,366
That was the only time Señor Lobo saw any action.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:0,55
At least we didn’t have to stick around for BS duty.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:55,109
They had another unit waiting in reserve to clean up.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:109,167
I guess the brass figured we’d done enough for one day.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:167,262
We marched ten miles to the east, set up a bivouac with watchtowers and concertainer 10 walls.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:262,282
I was so damn beat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:282,426
I don’t remember the chem shower, turning in my gear to be disinfected, turning in my weapon for inspection: not one jam, not the whole unit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[310]:426,471
I don’t even remember slipping into my bag.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:0,53
They let us sleep as late as we wanted the next day.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:53,76
That was pretty sweet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:76,154
Eventually the voices woke me up; everyone jawing, laughing, telling stories.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:154,209
It was a different vibe, one-eighty from two days ago.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:209,396
I couldn’t really put a finger on what I was feeling, maybe it was what the president said about “reclaiming our future.” I just knew I felt good, better than I had the entire war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:396,442
I knew it was gonna be a real, long-ass road.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[311]:442,588
I knew our campaign across America was just beginning, but, hey, as the prez said later that first night, it was finally the beginning of the end.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[312]
AINSWORTH, NEBRASKA, USA
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[313]:0,46
[Darnell Hackworth is a shy, soft-spoken man.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[313]:46,140
He and his wife run a retirement farm for the four-legged veterans of the army’s K-9 Corps.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[313]:140,222
Ten years ago farms like these could be found in almost every state in the union.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[313]:222,254
Now, this is the only one left.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[314]:0,39
They never get enough credit, I think.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[314]:39,211
There is that story Dax, nice little children’s book, but it’s pretty simplistic, and it’s only about one Dalmatian that helped an orphan kid find his way to safety.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[314]:211,343
“Dax” wasn’t even in the military, and helping lost children was a tiny fraction of dogs’ overall contribution to the fight.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:0,88
The first thing they used dogs for was triage, letting them sniff for who was infected.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:88,178
Most countries were just copying the Israeli method of sending people past dogs in cages.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:178,294
You always had to keep them in cages, otherwise they might attack the person, or each other, or even their handler.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:294,364
There was a lot of that, early in the war, dogs just going ballistic.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:364,416
It didn’t matter if they were police or military.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:416,479
It’s that instinct, that involuntary, almost genetic terror.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:479,531
Fight or flight, and those dogs were bred to fight.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:531,598
A lot of handlers lost hands, arms, a lot of throats got torn out.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:598,629
Can’t blame the dogs for it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[315]:629,732
In fact, that instinct was what the Israelis were counting on, and it probably saved millions of lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[316]:0,88
It was a great program, but, again, just a fraction of what dogs were truly capable of.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[316]:88,257
Whereas the Israelis and, after them, a lot of other countries only tried to exploit that terror instinct, we thought we could integrate it into their regular training.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[316]:257,346
And why not, we learned to do it for ourselves, and are we really that much more evolved?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:0,30
It all came down to training.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:30,124
You had to start young; even the most disciplined, prewar veterans were hardwired berserkers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:124,205
The pups born after the crisis came out of the womb literally smelling the dead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:205,320
It was in the air, not enough for us to detect, but just a few molecules, an introduction on a subconscious level.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:320,380
That’s not to say it made all of them automatic warriors.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:380,442
The initial induction was the first and most important phase.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:442,551
You took a group of pups, a random group, or even a whole litter, put them in a room divided by a wire mesh.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:551,597
They’re on one side, Zack’s on the other.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:597,644
You didn’t have to wait long for a reaction.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:644,674
The first group we called Bs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:674,712
They’d start whimpering or howling.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:712,730
They’d lost it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:730,761
They were nothing like the As.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:761,817
Those pups would lock eyes with Zack, that was the key.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[317]:817,1001
They’d stand their ground, bare their teeth, and let out this low growl that said, “Back the fuck off!” They could control themselves, and that was the foundation of our program.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:0,90
Now, just because they could control themselves didn’t mean that we could control them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:90,156
Basic training was pretty much like the standard, prewar program.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:156,178
Could they handle PT?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:178,206
1 Could they follow orders?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:206,276
Did they have the intelligence, and the discipline, to make soldiers?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:276,333
It was hard going, and we had a 60 percent washout rate.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:333,410
It wasn’t uncommon for a recruit to be badly injured, perhaps even killed.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:410,524
A lot of people nowadays call that inhumane, though they don’t seem to have the same sympathy for the handlers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:524,638
Yeah, we had to do it, too, right alongside the dogs, right from day one of Basic, through ten more weeks of AIT.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:638,699
2 It was hard training, especially the Live Enemy Exercises.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:699,855
You know we were the first ones to use Zack in our field training, before the infantry, before the Special Forces, even before the Zoomies at Willow Creek?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[318]:855,948
It was the only way to really know if you could hack it, both as an individual and as a team.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:0,65
How else could you have sent them on so many different missions?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:65,129
There were Lures, the kind that the Battle of Hope made famous.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:129,216
Pretty simple stuff; your partner hunts for Zack, then leads him into our firing line.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:216,299
Ks on early missions used to be fast, run in, bark, then jam it for the kill zone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:299,333
Later, they got more comfortable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:333,453
They learned to stay just a few feet ahead, backing away slowly, making sure they herded the maximum amount of targets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[319]:453,497
In that way, they actually called the shots.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[320]:0,24
There were also Decoys.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[320]:24,119
Let’s say you were setting up a firing line but you didn’t want Zack to show up too early.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[320]:119,210
Your partner would circle around the infested zone and only start barking on the far side.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[320]:210,301
That worked with a lot of engagements, and it opened the door for the “Lemming” tactic.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:0,169
During the Denver push, there was a tall building where a couple hundred refugees had accidentally been locked in with the infection and were now completely reanimated.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:169,354
Before our guys could storm the entrance, one of the Ks had his own idea to run up to the roof of a building across the street and start barking to draw Zack up onto the higher floors.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:354,378
It worked like a dream.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:378,472
The Gs made it up to the roof, saw their prey, made for him, and went spilling over the side.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:472,524
After Denver, Lemming went right into the playbook.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:524,588
Even the infantry started using it when Ks weren’t available.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[321]:588,705
It wasn’t uncommon to see a grunt standing on the roof of a building, calling out to an infested building close by.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:0,85
But the primary and most common mission of any K team was scouting, both SC and LRP.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:85,168
SC is Sweep and Clear, just attached to a regular unit, like conventional warfare.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:168,209
That’s where training really paid off.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:209,326
Not only could they sniff Zack out miles before us, but the sounds they made always told you exactly what to expect.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:326,429
You could tell everything you needed to know by the pitch of the growl, and the frequency of the bark.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:429,502
Sometimes, when silence was required, body language worked just as well.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:502,579
The arch of the K’s back, the raising of dander was all you needed to see.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:579,691
After a few missions, any competent handler, and we had no other kind, could read his partner’s every signal.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:691,786
Scouts finding a ghoul half submerged in mud or legless among tall grass saved a lot of lives.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[322]:786,916
I can’t tell you how many times a grunt would thank us personally for spotting a concealed G that might have taken his foot off.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:0,142
LRP was Long Range Patrol, when your partner would scout far beyond your lines, sometimes even traveling for days, to recon an infested area.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:142,286
They wore a special harness with a video uplink and GPS tracker that gave you real-time intel on the exact number and position of your targets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:286,409
You could overlay Zack’s position on a preexisting map, coordinating what your partner saw with his position on the GPS.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:409,522
I guess, from a technical side, it was pretty amazing, real-time hard intel like we used to have before the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:522,542
The brass loved it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:542,598
I didn’t; I was always too concerned with my partner.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:598,745
I can’t tell you how stressful that was, to be standing in some computer-filled, air-conditioned room—safe, comfortable, and totally helpless.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:745,850
Later harness models had radio uplinks, so a handler could relay orders or, at least, abort the mission.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:850,876
I never worked with them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:876,929
Teams had to be trained on those from the beginning.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:929,978
You couldn’t go back and retrain a seasoned K.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:978,1022
You couldn’t teach an old dog new tricks.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:1022,1039
Sorry, bad joke.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:1039,1251
I heard a lot of those from the intel pukes; standing behind them as they watched the damn monitor, mentally stroking it to the wonders of their new “Data Orientation Asset.” They thought they were so witty.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[323]:1251,1293
Real fun for us to have DOA as an acronym.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[324]
 
