/html/body/div/div[15]/p[387]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[388]
In order to understand how we became a “religious state,” and how that state began with a man like me, you have to understand the nature of our war against the undead.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:0,71
As with so many other conflicts, our greatest ally was General Winter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:71,217
The biting cold, lengthened and strengthened by the planet’s darkened skies, gave us the time we needed to prepare our homeland for liberation.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:217,281
Unlike the United States, we were fighting a war on two fronts.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:281,359
We had the Ural barrier in the west, and the Asian swarms from the southeast.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:359,436
Siberia had been stabilized, finally, but was by no means completely secure.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:436,552
We had so many refugees from India and China, so many frozen ghouls that thawed, and continue to thaw, each spring.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[389]:552,694
We needed those winter months to reorganize our forces, marshal our population, inventory and distribute our vast stocks of military hardware.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[390]:0,56
We didn’t have the war production of other countries.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[390]:56,183
There was no Department of Strategic Resources in Russia: no industry other than finding enough food to keep our people alive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[390]:183,247
What we did have was our legacy of a military industrial state.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[390]:247,648
I know you in the West have always laughed at us for this “folly.” “Paranoid Ivan”—that’s what you called us—“building tanks and guns while his people cry out for cars and butter.” Yes, the Soviet Union was backward and inefficient and yes, it did bankrupt our economy on mountains of military might, but when the motherland needed them, those mountains were what saved her children.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[391]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[392]:0,55
[He refers to the faded poster on the wall behind him.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[392]:55,193
It shows the ghostly image of an old Soviet soldier reaching down from heaven to hand a crude submachine gun to a grateful young Russian.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[392]:193,274
The caption underneath reads “Dyedooshka, Spaciba” (Thank you, Grandfather).]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[393]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[394]:0,62
I was a chaplain with the Thirty-second Motor Rifle division.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[394]:62,140
We were a Category D unit; fourth-class equipment, the oldest in our arsenal.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[394]:140,269
We looked like extras in an old Great Patriotic War movie with our PPSH submachine guns and our bolt-action Mosin-Nagant rifles.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[394]:269,324
We didn’t have your fancy, new battle dress uniform.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[394]:324,472
We wore the tunics of our grandfathers: rough, moldy, moth-eaten wool that could barely keep the cold out, and did nothing to protect against bites.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[395]:0,105
We had a very high casualty rate, most of it in urban combat, and most of that due to faulty ammunition.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[395]:105,240
Those rounds were older than us; some of them had been sitting in crates, open to the elements, since before Stalin breathed his last.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[395]:240,359
You never knew when a “Cugov” would happen, when your weapon would “click” at the moment a ghoul was upon you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[395]:359,421
That happened a lot in the Thirty-second Motor Rifle division.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[396]:0,49
We weren’t as neat and organized as your army.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[396]:49,166
We didn’t have your tight, light little Raj-Singh squares or your frugal “one shot, one kill” combat doctrine.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[396]:166,202
Our battles were sloppy and brutal.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[396]:202,376
We plastered the enemy in DShK heavy machine-gun fire, drowned them with flamethrowers and Katyusha rockets, and crushed them under the treads of our prehistoric T-34 tanks.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[396]:376,449
It was inefficient and wasteful and resulted in too many needless deaths.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[397]:0,49
Ufa was the first major battle of our offensive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[397]:49,146
It became the reason we stopped going into the cities and started walling them up during winter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[397]:146,319
We learned a lot of lessons those first months, charging headlong into the rubble after hours of merciless artillery, fighting block by block, house by house, room by room.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[397]:319,406
There were always too many zombies, too many misfires, and always too many bitten boys.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:0,46
We didn’t have L pills 1 like in your army.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:46,96
The only way to deal with infection was a bullet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:96,135
But who was going to pull the trigger?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:135,169
Certainly not the other soldiers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:169,271
To kill your comrade, even in cases as merciful as infection, was too reminiscent of the decimations.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:271,301
That was the irony of it all.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:301,424
The decimations had given our armed forces the strength and discipline to do anything we asked of them, anything but that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[398]:424,534
To ask, or even order, one soldier to kill another was crossing a line that might have sparked another mutiny.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[399]:0,94
For a while the responsibility rested with the leadership, the officers and senior sergeants.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[399]:94,144
We couldn’t have made a more damaging decision.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[399]:144,332
To have to look into the faces of these men, these boys whom you were responsible for, whom you fought with side by side, shared bread and blankets, saved his life or have him save yours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[399]:332,420
Who can focus on the monumental burden of leadership after having to commit such an act?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[400]:0,69
We began to see a noticeable degradation among our field commanders.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[400]:69,168
Dereliction of duty, alcoholism, suicide—suicide became almost epidemic among the officer corps.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[400]:168,300
Our division lost four experienced leaders, three junior lieutenants, and a major, all during the first week of our first campaign.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[400]:300,409
Two of the lieutenants shot themselves, one right after committing the deed, and the other later that night.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[400]:409,630
The third platoon leader chose a more passive method, what we began to call “suicide by combat.” He volunteered for increasingly dangerous missions, acting more like a reckless enlisted man than a responsible leader.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[400]:630,698
He died trying to take on a dozen ghouls with nothing but a bayonet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:0,28
Major Kovpak just vanished.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:28,55
No one knows exactly when.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:55,94
We knew he couldn’t have been taken.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:94,192
The area was thoroughly swept and no one, absolutely no one left the perimeter without an escort.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:192,228
We all knew what probably happened.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:228,358
Colonel Savichev put out an official statement that the major had been sent on a long-range recon mission and had never returned.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:358,437
He even went so far as to recommend him for a first-class Order of the Rodina.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:437,563
You can’t stop the rumors, and nothing is worse for a unit’s morale than to know that one of their officers had deserted.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:563,606
I could not blame the man, I still cannot.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:606,646
Kovpak was a good man, a strong leader.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:646,721
Before the crisis he had done three tours in Chechnya and one in Dagestan.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:721,941
When the dead began to rise, he not only prevented his company from revolting, but led them all, on foot, carrying both supplies and wounded from Curta in the Salib Mountains all the way to Manaskent on the Caspian Sea.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:941,990
Sixty-five days, thirty-seven major engagements.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:990,1004
Thirty-seven!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:1004,1155
He could have become an instructor—he’d more than earned the right—and had even been asked by STAVKA because of his extensive combat experience.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:1155,1213
But no, he volunteered for an immediate return to action.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:1213,1240
And now he was a deserter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[401]:1240,1439
They used to call this “the Second Decimation,” the fact that almost one in every ten officers killed themselves in those days, a decimation that almost brought our war effort to a crushing halt.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:0,96
The logical alternative, the only one, was to therefore let the boys commit the act themselves.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:96,224
I can still remember their faces, dirty and pimply, their red-rimmed eyes wide as they closed their mouths around their rifles.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:224,249
What else could be done?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:249,452
It wasn’t long before they began to kill themselves in groups, all those who’d been bitten in a battle gathering at the field hospital to synchronize the moment when they would all pull the trigger.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:452,520
I guess it was comforting, knowing that they weren’t dying alone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:520,572
It was probably the only comfort they could expect.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[402]:572,611
They certainly didn’t get it from me.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[403]:0,71
I was a religious man in a country that had long since lost its faith.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[403]:71,381
Decades of communism followed by materialistic democracy had left this generation of Russians with little knowledge of, or need for, “the opium of the masses.” As a chaplain, my duties were mainly to collect letters from the condemned boys to their families, and to distribute any vodka I managed to find.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[403]:381,507
It was a next-to-useless existence, I knew, and the way our country was headed, I doubted anything would occur to change that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:0,100
It was right after the battle for Kostroma, just a few weeks before the official assault on Moscow.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:100,170
I had come to the field hospital to give last rights to the infected.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:170,244
They had been set apart, some badly mauled, some still healthy and lucid.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:244,301
The first boy couldn’t have been older than seventeen.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:301,352
He wasn’t bitten, that would have been merciful.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:352,442
The zombie had had its forearms ripped off by the treads of an SU-152 self-propelled gun.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:442,544
All that remained was hanging flesh and broken humerus bones, jagged at the edges, sharp like spears.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:544,636
They stabbed right through the boy’s tunic where whole hands would have just grabbed him.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:636,726
He was lying on a cot, bleeding from his belly, ashen-faced, rifle quivering in his hand.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:726,781
Next to him was a row of five other infected soldiers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:781,854
I went through the motions of telling them I would pray for their souls.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:854,895
They either shrugged or nodded politely.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:895,1029
I took their letters, as I’d always done, gave them a drink, and even passed out a couple cigarettes from their commanding officer.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1029,1105
Even though I’d done this many times, somehow I felt strangely different.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1105,1225
Something was stirring within me, a tense, tingling sensation that began to work its way up through my heart and lungs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1225,1343
I began to feel my whole body tremble as the soldiers all placed the muzzles of their weapons underneath their chins.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1343,1384
“On three,” the oldest of them said.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1384,1432
“One…two…” That was as far as they got.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1432,1489
The seventeen-year-old flew backward and hit the ground.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[404]:1489,1613
The others stared dumbfounded at the bullet hole in his forehead, then up to the smoking pistol in my hand, in God’s hand.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[405]:0,67
God was speaking to me, I could feel his words ringing in my head.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[405]:67,168
“No more sinning,” he told me, “no more souls resigned to hell.” It was so clear, so simple.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[405]:168,301
Officers killing soldiers had cost us too many good officers, and soldiers killing themselves had cost the Lord too many good souls.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[405]:301,495
Suicide was a sin, and we, his servants—those who had chosen to be his shepherds upon the earth—were the only ones who should bear the cross of releasing trapped souls from infected bodies!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[405]:495,703
That is what I told division commander after he discovered what I’d done, and that is the message that spread first to every chaplain in the field and then to every civilian priest throughout Mother Russia.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[406]:0,170
What later became known as the act of “Final Purification” was only the first step of a religious fervor that would surpass even the Iranian revolution of the 1980s.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[406]:170,231
God knew his children had been denied his love for too long.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[406]:231,269
They needed direction, courage, hope!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[406]:269,420
You could say that it is the reason we emerged from that war as a nation of faith, and have continued to rebuild our state, on the basis of that faith.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[407]
Is there any truth to the stories of that philosophy being perverted for political reasons?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[408]
[Pause.] I don’t understand.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[409]
The president declared himself head of the Church…
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[410]
Can’t a national leader feel God’s love?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[411]
But what about organizing priests into “death squads,” and assassinating people under the premise of “purifying infected victims”?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[412]
[Pause.] I don’t know what you’re talking about.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[413]:0,54
Isn’t that why you eventually fell out with Moscow?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[413]:54,85
Isn’t that why you’re here?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[414]:0,24
[There is a long pause.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[414]:24,69
We hear the sounds of footsteps approaching.
