====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[419]
ABOARD USS HOLO KAI, OFF THE COAST OF THE HAWAIIAN ISLANDS
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:0,72
[Deep Glider 7 looks more like a twin fuselage aircraft than a minisub.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:72,167
I lie on my stomach in the starboard hull, looking out through a thick, transparent nose cone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:167,250
My pilot, Master Chief Petty Officer Michael Choi, waves at me from the port hull.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:250,335
Choi is one of the “old-timers,” possibly the most experienced diver in the U.S.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:335,382
Navy’s Deep Submergence Combat Corps (DSCC).
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:382,482
His gray temples and weathered crow’s-feet clash violently with his almost adolescent enthusiasm.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[420]:482,626
As the mother ship lowers us into the choppy Pacific, I detect a trace of “surfer dude” bleeding through Choi’s otherwise neutral accent.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[421]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[422]:0,20
My war never ended.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[422]:20,72
If anything, you could say it’s still escalating.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[422]:72,152
Every month we expand our operations and improve our material and human assets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[422]:152,301
They say there are still somewhere between twenty and thirty million of them, still washing up on beaches, or getting snagged in fishermen’s nets.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[422]:301,400
You can’t work an offshore oil rig or repair a transatlantic cable without running into a swarm.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[422]:400,537
That’s what this dive is about: trying to find them, track them, and predict their movements so maybe we can have some advance warning.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[423]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[424]:0,43
[We hit the whitecaps with a jarring thud.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[424]:43,144
Choi grins, checks his instruments, and shifts the channels on his radio from me to the mother ship.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[424]:144,253
The water before my observation dome froths white for a second, then gives way to light blue as we submerge.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[425]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[426]:0,133
You’re not going to ask me about scuba gear or titanium shark suits, are you, because that crap’s got nothing to do with my war?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[426]:133,221
Spear guns and bang sticks and zombie river nets…I can’t help you with any of that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[426]:221,262
If you want civilians, talk to civilians.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[427]
But the military did use those methods.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:0,64
Only for brown water ops, and almost exclusively by army pukes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:64,154
Personally, I’ve never worn a mesh suit or a scuba rig…well…at least not in combat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:154,179
My war was strictly ADS.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:179,204
Atmospheric Diving Suit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:204,271
Kind of like a space suit and a suit of armor all rolled into one.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:271,395
The technology actually goes back a couple hundred years, when some guy 1 invented a barrel with a faceplate and arm holes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:395,463
After that you had stuff like the Tritonia and the Neufeldt-Kuhnke.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:463,556
They looked like something out of an old 1950s sci-fi movie, “Robby the Robot” and shit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[428]:556,630
It all kinda fell by the wayside when…do you really care about all this?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[429]
Yes, please…
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[430]:0,75
Well, that sort of technology fell by the wayside when scuba was invented.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[430]:75,168
It only made a comeback when divers had to go deep, real deep, to work on offshore oil rigs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[430]:168,311
You see…the deeper you go, the greater the pressure; the greater the pressure, the more dangerous it is for scuba or similar mixed-gas rigs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[430]:311,649
You’ve got to spend days, sometimes weeks, in a decompression chamber, and if, for some reason, you have to shoot up to the surface…you get the bends, gas bubbles in the blood, in the brain…and we’re not even talking about long-term health hazards like bone necrosis, soaking your body with shit nature never intended to be there.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[431]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[432]
[He pauses to check his instruments.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[433]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[434]
The safest way to dive, to go deeper, to stay down longer, was to enclose your whole body in a bubble of surface pressure.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[435]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[436]
[He gestures to the compartments around us.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[437]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[438]:0,96
Just like we are now—safe, protected, still on the surface as far as our bodies’ concerned.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[438]:96,185
That’s what an ADS does, its depth and duration only limited by armor and life support.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[439]
So it’s like a personal submarine?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[440]:0,103
“Submersible.” A submarine can stay down for years, maintaining its own power, making its own air.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[440]:103,199
A submersible can only make short duration dives, like World War II subs or what we’re in now.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[441]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[442]
[The water begins to darken, deepening to a purplish ink.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[443]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[444]:0,125
The very nature of an ADS, the fact that it’s really just a suit of armor, makes it ideal for blue and black water combat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[444]:125,192
I’m not knocking soft suits, you know, shark or other mesh rigs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[444]:192,455
They’ve got ten times the maneuverability, the speed, the agility, but they’re strictly shallow water at best, and if for some reason a couple of those fuckers get ahold of you…I’ve seen mesh divers with broken arms, broken ribs, three with broken necks.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[444]:455,544
Drowning…if your air line was punctured or the regulator’s ripped out of your mouth.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[444]:544,656
Even in a hard helmet on a mesh-lined dry suit, all they’d have to do is hold you down, let your air run out.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[444]:656,780
I’ve seen too many guys go out that way, or else try to race for the surface and let an embolism finish what Zack started.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[445]
Did that happen a lot to mesh suit divers?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:0,69
Sometimes, especially in the beginning, but it never happened to us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:69,107
There was no risk of physical danger.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:107,209
Both your body and your life support are encased in a cast-aluminum or high-strength composite shell.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:209,254
Most models’ joints are steel or titanium.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:254,449
No matter which way Zack turned your arms, even if he managed to get a solid grip, which is hard considering how smooth and round everything is, it was physically impossible to break off a limb.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:449,604
If for some reason you need to jet up to the surface, just jettison your ballast or your thruster pack, if you had one…all suits are positively buoyant.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:604,635
They pop right up like a cork.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:635,706
The only risk might be if Zack were clinging to you during the ascent.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:706,813
A couple times I’ve had buddies surface with uninvited passengers hanging on for dear life…or undeath.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[446]:813,824
[Chuckles.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[447]:0,49
Balloon ascents almost never happened in combat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[447]:49,112
Most ADS models have forty-eight hours emergency life support.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[447]:112,314
No matter how many Gs dog-piled you, no matter if a hunk of debris came crumbling down or your leg got snagged in an underwater cable, you could sit tight, snug and safe, and just wait for the cavalry.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[447]:314,423
No one ever dives alone, and I think the longest any ADS diver has ever had to cool his heels was six hours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[447]:423,668
There were times, more than I can count on my fingers, where one of us would get snagged, report it, then follow up by saying that there was no immediate danger, and that the rest of the team should assist only after accomplishing their mission.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[448]:0,20
You say ADS models.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[448]:20,49
Was there more than one type?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[449]:0,70
We had a bunch: civilian, military, old, new…well…relatively new.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[449]:70,161
We couldn’t build any wartime models, so we had to work with what was already available.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[449]:161,287
Some of the older ones dated back to the seventies, the JIMs and SAMs. I’m really glad I never had to operate any of those.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[449]:287,439
They only had universal joints and portholes instead of a face bowl, at least on the early JIMs. I knew one guy, from the British Special Boat Service.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[449]:439,552
He had these mondo blood blisters all along his inner thighs from where the JIM’s leg joints pinched his skin.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[449]:552,614
Kick-ass divers, the SBS, but I’d never swap jobs with them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:0,24
We had three basic U.S.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:24,90
Navy models: the Hardsuit 1200, the 2000, and the Mark 1 Exosuit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:90,117
That was my baby, the exo.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:117,212
You wanna talk about sci-fi, this thing looked like it was made to fight giant space termites.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:212,309
It was much slimmer than either of the two hardsuits, and light enough that you could even swim.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:309,556
That was the major advantage over the hardsuit, actually over all other ADS systems. To be able to operate above your enemy, even without a power sled or thruster packs, that more than made up for the fact that you couldn’t scratch your itches.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[450]:556,686
The hardsuits were big enough to allow your arms to be pulled into the central cavity to allow you to operate secondary equipment.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[451]
What kind of equipment?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[452]:0,36
Lights, video, side scanning sonar.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[452]:36,107
The hardsuits were full-service units, exos were the bargain basement.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[452]:107,173
You didn’t have to worry about a lot of readouts and machinery.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[452]:173,253
You didn’t have any of the distractions or the multitasking of the hardsuits.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[452]:253,350
The exo was sleek and simple, allowing you to focus on your weapon and the field in front of you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[453]
What kind of weapons did you use?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:0,81
At first we had the M-9, kind of a cheap, modified, knockoff of the Russian APS.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:81,157
I say “modified” because no ADS had anything close to resembling hands.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:157,222
You either had four-pronged claws or simple, industrial pincers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:222,340
Both worked as hand-to-hand weapons—just grab a G’s head and squeeze—but they made it impossible to fire a gun.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:340,407
The M-9 was fixed to your forearm and could be fired electrically.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:407,514
It had a laser pointer for accuracy and air-encased cartridges that fired these four-inch-long steel rods.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:514,600
The major problem was that they were basically designed for shallow water operations.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:600,654
At the depth we needed, they imploded like eggshells.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:654,790
About a year in we got a much more efficient model, the M-11, actually invented by the same guy who invented both the hardsuit and exo.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:790,869
I hope that crazy Canuck got an assload of medals for what he’s done for us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:869,949
The only problem with it was that DeStRes thought production was too expensive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[454]:949,1068
They kept telling us that between our claws and preexisting construction tools, we had more than enough to handle Zack.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[455]
What changed their minds?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:0,7
Troll.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:7,239
We were in the North Sea, repairing that Norwegian natural gas platform, and suddenly there they were…We’d expected some kind of attack—the noise and light of the construction site always attracted at least a handful of them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:239,276
We didn’t know a swarm was nearby.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:276,367
One of our sentries sounded off, we headed for his beacon, and we were suddenly inundated.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:367,416
Horrible thing to fight hand-to-hand underwater.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:416,501
The bottom churns up, your visibility is shot, like fighting inside a glass of milk.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:501,671
Zombies don’t just die when you hit them, most of the time they disintegrate, fragments of muscle, organ, brain matter, mixed up with the silt and swirling around you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:671,903
Kids today…fuckin’ A, I sound like my pops, but it’s true, the kids today, the new ADS divers in the Mark 3s and 4s, they have this “ZeVDeK”—Zero Visibility Detection Kit—with color-imaging sonar and low-light optics.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:903,999
The picture is relayed through a heads-up display right on your face bowl like a fighter plane.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:999,1090
Throw in a pair of stereo hydrophones and you’ve got a real sensory advantage over Zack.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:1090,1135
That was not the case when I first went exo.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[456]:1135,1240
We couldn’t see, we couldn’t hear—we couldn’t even feel if a G was trying to grab us from behind.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[457]
Why was that?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[458]:0,73
Because the one fundamental flaw of an ADS is complete tactile blackout.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[458]:73,207
The simple fact that the suit is hard means you can’t feel anything from the outside world, even if a G has his hands right on you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[458]:207,356
Unless Zack is actively tugging, trying to pull you back or flip you around, you may not know he’s there until his face is right up against yours.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[458]:356,495
That night at Troll…our helmet lights only made the problem worse by throwing up a glare that was only broken by an undead hand or face.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[458]:495,670
That was the only time I was ever spooked…not scared, you understand, just spooked, swinging in this liquid chalk and suddenly a rotting face is jammed against my face bowl.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:0,135
The civilian oil workers, they wouldn’t go back to work, even under threat of reprisals, until we, their escorts, were better armed.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:135,211
They’d lost enough of their people already, ambushed out of the darkness.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:211,258
Can’t imagine what that must have been like.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:258,451
You’re in this dry suit, working in near pitch-black, eyes stinging from the light of the welding torch, body numb from the cold or else burning from the hot water pumped through the system.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:451,492
Suddenly you feel these hands, or teeth.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:492,563
You struggle, call for help, try to fight or swim as they pull you up.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:563,661
Maybe a few body parts will rise to the surface, maybe they’ll just pull up a severed lifeline.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:661,722
That was how the DSCC came into being as an official outfit.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:722,793
Our first mission was to protect the rig divers, keep the oil flowing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[459]:793,855
Later we expanded to beachhead sanitation and harbor clearing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[460]
What is beachhead sanitation?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[461]:0,44
Basically, helping the jarheads get ashore.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[461]:44,193
What we learned during Bermuda, our first amphibious landing, was that the beachhead was coming under constant attack by Gs walking out of the surf.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[461]:193,356
We had to establish a perimeter, a semicircular net around the proposed landing area that was deep enough for ships to pass over, but high enough to keep out Zack.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[462]:0,27
That’s where we came in.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[462]:27,160
Two weeks before the landings took place, a ship would anchor several miles offshore and start banging away with their active sonar.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[462]:160,202
That was to draw Zack away from the beach.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[463]
Wouldn’t that sonar also lure in zombies from deeper water?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:0,97
The brass told us that was an “acceptable risk.” I think they didn’t have anything better.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:97,155
That’s why it was an ADS op, too risky for mesh divers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:155,291
You knew that masses were gathering under that pinging ship, and that once they went silent, you’d be the brightest target out there.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:291,365
It actually turned out to be the closest thing we ever had to a cakewalk.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:365,477
The attack frequency was the lowest by far, and when the nets were up, they had an almost perfect success rate.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:477,599
All you needed was a skeleton force to keep a constant vigil, maybe snipe the occasional G that tried to climb the fence.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:599,649
They didn’t really need us for this kind of op.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[464]:649,717
After the first three landings, they went back to using mesh divers.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[465]
And harbor clearing?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:0,25
That was not a cakewalk.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:25,161
That was in the final stages of the war, when it wasn’t just about opening a beachhead, but reopening harbors for deepwater shipping.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:161,296
That was a massive, combined operation: mesh divers, ADS units, even civilian volunteers with nothing but a scuba rig and a spear gun.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:296,419
I helped clear Charleston, Norfolk, Boston, freakin’ Boston, and the mother of all subsurface nightmares, the Hero City.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:419,590
I know grunts like to bitch about fighting to clear a city, but imagine a city underwater, a city of sunken ships and cars and planes and every kind of debris imaginable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:590,735
During the evacuation, when a lot of container ships were trying to make as much room as they could, a lot of them dumped their cargo overboard.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:735,795
Couches, toaster ovens, mountains and mountains of clothes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:795,849
Plasma TVs always crunched when you walked over them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:849,880
I always imagined it was bone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:880,996
I also imagined I could see Zack behind each washer and dryer, climbing over each pile of smashed air conditioners.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:996,1107
Sometimes it was just my imagination, but sometimes…The worst…the worst was having to clear a sunken ship.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:1107,1180
There were always a few that had gone down within the harbor boundaries.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[466]:1180,1296
