/html/body/div/div[15]/p[514]
QUEBEC, CANADA
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[515]:0,83
[The small farmhouse has no wall, no bars on the windows, and no lock on the door.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[515]:83,170
When I ask the owner about his vulnerability he simply chuckles and resumes his lunch.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[515]:170,284
Andre Renard, brother of the legendary war hero Emil Renard, has requested that I keep his exact location secret.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[515]:284,505
“I don’t care if the dead find me,” he says without feeling, “but I care very little for the living.” The former French national immigrated to this place after the official end of hostilities in western Europe.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[515]:505,583
Despite numerous invitations from the French government, he has not returned.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[516]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[517]:0,289
Everyone else is a liar, everyone who claims that their campaign was “the hardest of the entire war.” All those ignorant peacocks who beat their chests and brag about “mountain warfare” or “jungle warfare” or “urban warfare.” Cities, oh how they love to brag about cities!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[517]:289,355
“Nothing more terrifying than fighting in a city!” Oh really?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[517]:355,374
Try underneath one.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[518]:0,102
Do you know why the Paris skyline was devoid of skyscrapers, I mean the prewar, proper Paris skyline?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[518]:102,217
Do you know why they stuck all those glass and steel monstrosities out in La Defense, so far from the city center?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[518]:217,335
Yes, there’s aesthetics, a sense of continuity and civic pride…not like that architectural mongrel called London.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[518]:335,509
But the truth, the logical, practical, reason for keeping Paris free from American-style monoliths, is that the earth beneath their feet is simply too tunneled to support it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[519]:0,160
There are Roman tombs, quarries that supplied limestone for much of the city, even World War II bunkers used by the Resistance and yes, there was a Resistance!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[519]:160,290
Then there is the modern Metro, the telephone lines, the gas mains, the water pipes…and through it all, you have the catacombs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[519]:290,425
Roughly six million bodies were buried there, taken from the prerevolution cemeteries, where corpses were just tossed in like rubbish.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[519]:425,512
The catacombs contained entire walls of skulls and bones arranged in macabre patterns.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[519]:512,617
It was even functional in places where interlocking bones held back mounds of loose remains behind them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[519]:617,663
The skulls always seemed to be laughing at me.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[520]:0,91
I don’t think I can blame the civilians who tried to survive in that subterranean world.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[520]:91,187
They didn’t have the civilian survival manual back then, they didn’t have Radio Free Earth.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[520]:187,211
It was the Great Panic.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[520]:211,336
Maybe a few souls who thought they knew those tunnels decided to make a go of it, a few more followed them, then a few more.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[520]:336,500
The word spread, “it’s safe underground.” A quarter million in all, that’s what the bone counters have determined, two hundred and fifty thousand refugees.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[520]:500,679
Maybe if they had been organized, thought to bring food and tools, even had enough sense to seal the entrances behind them and make damn sure those coming in weren’t infected…
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[521]:0,75
How can anyone claim that their experience can compare to what we endured?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[521]:75,202
The darkness and the stink…we had almost no night vision goggles, just one pair per platoon, and that’s if you were lucky.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[521]:202,270
Spare batteries were in short supply for our electric torches, too.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[521]:270,401
Sometimes there was only one working unit for an entire squad, just for the point man, cutting the darkness with a red-coated beam.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[522]:0,123
The air was toxic with sewage, chemicals, rotting flesh…the gas masks were a joke, most of the filters had long expired.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[522]:123,288
We wore anything we could find, old military models, or firefighting hoods that covered your entire head, made you sweat like a pig, made you deaf as well as blind.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[522]:288,430
You never knew where you were, staring through that misty visor, hearing the muffled voices of your squad mates, the crackle of your radioman.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[523]:0,90
We had to use hardwired sets, you see, because airwave transmissions were too unreliable.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[523]:90,143
We used old telephone wire, copper, not fiber optic.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[523]:143,233
We would just rip it off the conduits and keep massive rolls with us to extend our range.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[523]:233,336
It was the only way to keep in contact, and, most of the time, the only way to keep from becoming lost.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[524]:0,31
It was so easy to become lost.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[524]:31,242
All the maps were prewar and didn’t take into account the modifications the survivors had made, all the interconnecting tunnels and alcoves, the holes in the floor that would suddenly open up in front of you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[524]:242,446
You would lose your way, at least once a day, sometimes more, and then have to trace your way back down the communications wire, check your location on the map, and try to figure out what had gone wrong.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[524]:446,513
Sometimes it was only a few minutes, sometimes hours, or even days.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[525]:0,113
When another squad was being attacked, you would hear their cries over the radio or echoing through the tunnels.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[525]:113,156
The acoustics were evil; they taunted you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[525]:156,201
Screams and moans came from every direction.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[525]:201,245
You never knew where they were coming from.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[525]:245,335
At least with the radio, you could try, maybe, to get a fix on your comrades’ position.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[525]:335,422
If they weren’t panicked, if they knew where they were, if you knew where you were…
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[526]:0,194
The running: you dash through the passageways, bash your head on the ceiling, crawl on your hands and knees, praying to the Virgin with all your might for them to hold for just a little longer.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[526]:194,315
You get to their position, find it is the wrong one, an empty chamber, and the screams for help are still a long way off.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[527]:0,64
And when you arrive, maybe to find nothing but bones and blood.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[527]:64,242
Maybe you are lucky to find the zombies still there, a chance for vengeance…if it has taken a long time to reach them, that vengeance must now include your reanimated friends.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[527]:242,256
Close combat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[527]:256,272
Close like so…
