====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[556]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[557]:0,72
They called it “the road to New York” and it was a long, long road.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[557]:72,129
We had three main Army Groups: North, Center, and South.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[557]:129,410
The grand strategy was to advance as one across the Great Plains, across the Midwest, then break off at the Appalachians, the wings sweeping north and south, shoot for Maine and Florida, then grind across the coast and link up with AG Center as they slogged it over the mountains.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[557]:410,430
It took three years.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[558]
Why so slow?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[559]:0,220
Dude, take your pick: foot transport, terrain, weather, enemies, battle doctrine…Doctrine was to advance as two solid lines, one behind the other, stretching from Canada to Aztlan…No, Mexico, it wasn’t Aztlan yet.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[559]:220,330
You know when a plane goes down, how all these firemen or whoever would check a field for pieces of wreckage?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[559]:330,415
They’d all go in a line, real slow, making sure not one inch of ground was missed.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[559]:415,428
That was us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[559]:428,497
We didn’t skip one damn inch between the Rockies and the Atlantic.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[559]:497,586
Whenever you spotted Zack, either in a group or just on his own, a FAR unit would halt…
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[560]
FAR?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:0,28
Force Appropriate Response.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:28,101
You couldn’t stop, like, the whole Army Group, for one or two zombies.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:101,290
A lot of the older Gs, the ones infected early in the war, they were starting to get pretty grody, all deflated, parts of their skulls starting to show, some bone poking through the flesh.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:290,386
Some of them couldn’t even stand anymore, and those are the ones you really had to watch for.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:386,475
They’d be crawling on their bellies toward you, or just thrashing facedown in the mud.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:475,631
You’d halt a section, a platoon, maybe even a company depending on how many you encountered, just enough to take ’em down and sanitize the battlefield.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:631,764
The hole your FAR unit left in the battle line was replaced by an equal force from the secondary line a click and a half behind you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:764,801
That way the front was never broken.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:801,857
We leapfrogged this way all the way across the country.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:857,905
It worked, no doubt, but man, it took its time.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:905,935
Night also put the brakes on.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[561]:935,1063
Once the sun dipped, no matter how confident you felt or how safe the area seemed, the show was over till dawn the next morning.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[562]:0,19
And there was fog.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[562]:19,74
I didn’t know fog could be so thick that far inland.
