/html/body/div/div[15]/p[563]:308,403
That was the start of the UN multinational force, but I was discharged long before those days.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[563]:403,506
For me, it always felt like hurry up and wait, creeping along through rough terrain or built-up areas.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[563]:506,565
Oh, and you wanna talk about speed bumps, try urban combat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[564]:0,53
The strategy was always to surround the target area.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[564]:53,246
We’d set up semipermanent defenses, recon with everything from satellites to sniffer Ks, do whatever we could to call Zack out, and go in only after we were sure no more of them were coming.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[564]:246,282
Smart and safe and relatively easy.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[564]:282,294
Yeah, right!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[565]:0,93
As far as surrounding the “area,” someone wanna tell me where that area actually begins?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[565]:93,182
Cities weren’t cities anymore, you know, they just grew out into this suburban sprawl.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[565]:182,367
Mrs. Ruiz, one of our medics, called it “in-fill.” She was in real estate before the war and explained that the hottest properties were always the land between two existing cities.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[565]:367,427
Freakin’ “in-fill,” we all learned to hate that term.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[565]:427,550
For us, it meant clearing block after block of burbland before we could even think of establishing a quarantine perimeter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[565]:550,632
Fast-food joints, shopping centers, endless miles of cheap, cookie-cutter housing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[566]:0,65
Even in winter, it’s not like everything was safe and snuggly.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[566]:65,92
I was in Army Group North.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[566]:92,137
At first I thought we were golden, you know.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[566]:137,260
Six months out of the year, I wouldn’t have to see a live G, eight months actually, given what wartime weather was like.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[566]:260,425
I thought, hey, once the temp drops, we’re little more than garbage men: find ’em, Lobo ’em, mark ’em for burial once the ground begins to thaw, no problem.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[566]:425,504
But I should be Lobo’d for thinking that Zack was the only bad guy out there.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[567]:0,60
We had quislings, just like the real thing, but winterized.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[567]:60,141
We had these Human Reclamation units, pretty much just glorified animal control.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[567]:141,304
They’d do their best to dart any quislings we came across, tie ’em down, ship ’em to rehabilitation clinics, back when we thought we could rehabilitate them.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:0,42
Ferals were a much more dangerous threat.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:42,118
A lot of them weren’t kids anymore, some were teenagers, some full grown.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:118,220
They were fast, smart, and if they chose fight instead of flight, they could really mess up your day.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:220,309
Of course, HR would always try and dart them, and, of course, that didn’t always work.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:309,447
When a two-hundred-pound feral bull is charging balls out for your ass, a couple CCs of tranq ain’t gonna drop him before he hits home.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:447,524
A lot of HRs got pretty badly smashed up, a few had to be tagged and bagged.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:524,590
