====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:590,644
If a dart didn’t stop a feral, we sure as hell did.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:644,716
Nothing screams as high as a feral with a PIE round burning in his gut.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:716,759
The HR pukes had a real problem with that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:759,874
They were all volunteers, all sticking to this code that human life, any human’s life, was worth trying to save.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:874,1028
I guess history sorta backed them up now, you know, seeing all those people that they managed to rehabilitate, all the ones we just woulda shot on sight.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[568]:1028,1112
If they had had the resources, they might have been able to do the same for animals.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:0,63
Man, feral packs, that freaked me out more than anything else.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:63,92
I’m not just talking dogs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:92,124
Dogs you knew how to deal with.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:124,163
Dogs always telegraphed their attacks.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:163,257
I’m talking “Flies” 3 : F-Lions, cats, like part mountain lion, part ice age saberfuck.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:257,400
Maybe they were mountain lions, some sure looked like them, or maybe just the spawn of house cats that had to be super badass just to make it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:400,478
I’ve heard that they grew bigger up north, some law of nature or evolution.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:478,562
4 I don’t really get the whole ecology thing, not past a few prewar nature shows.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:562,726
I hear it’s because rats were, like, the new cows; fast and smart enough to get away from Zack, livin’ on corpses, breeding by the millions in trees and ruins.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:726,836
They’d gotten pretty badass themselves, so anything tough enough to hunt them has to be a whole lot badder.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[569]:836,962
That’s an F-lion for you, about twice the size of a prewar puffball, teeth, claws, and a real, real jonesing for warm blood.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[570]
That must have been a hazard for the sniffer dogs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[571]:0,17
Are you kidding?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[571]:17,92
They loved it, even the little dachmutts, made ’em feel like dogs again.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[571]:92,160
I’m talking about us, getting jumped from a tree limb, or a roof.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[571]:160,283
They didn’t charge you like F-hounds, they just waited, took their sweet time until you were too close to raise a weapon.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[572]:0,60
Outside of Minneapolis, my squad was clearing a strip mall.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[572]:60,172
I was stepping through the window of a Starbucks and suddenly three of them leap at me from behind the counter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[572]:172,227
They knock me over, start tearing at my arms, my face.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[572]:227,255
How do you think I got this?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[573]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[574]
[He refers to the scar on his cheek.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[575]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[576]:0,55
I guess the only real casualty that day was my shorts.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[576]:55,258
Between the bite-proof BDUs and body armor we’d started wearing, the vest, the helmet…I hadn’t worn a hard cover in so long, you forget how uncomfortable it is when you’re used to going soft top.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[577]
Did ferals, feral people that is, know how to use firearms?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:0,76
They didn’t know how to do anything human, that’s why they were ferals.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:76,159
No, the body armor was for protection against some of the regular people we found.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:159,236
I’m not talking organized rebels, just the odd LaMOE, 5 Last Man on Earth.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:236,324
There was always one or two in every town, some dude, or chick, who managed to survive.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:324,466
I read somewhere that the United States had the highest number of them in the world, something about our individualistic nature or something.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:466,570
They hadn’t seen real people in so long, a lot of the initial shooting was just accidental or reflex.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:570,617
Most of the time we managed to talk them down.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[578]:617,718
Those we actually called RCs, Robinson Crusoes—that was the polite term for the ones who were cool.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[579]:0,89
The ones we called LaMOEs, those were the ones who were a little too used to being king.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[579]:89,254
King of what, I don’t know, Gs and quislings and crazy F-critters, but I guess in their mind they were living the good life, and here we were to take it all away.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[579]:254,280
That’s how I got nailed.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:0,47
We were closing on the Sears Tower in Chicago.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:47,104
Chicago, that was enough nightmares for three lifetimes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:104,250
It was the middle of winter, wind whipping off the lake so hard you could barely stand, and suddenly I felt Thor’s hammer smash me in the head.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:250,290
Slug from a high-powered hunting rifle.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:290,351
I never complained about our hard covers anymore after that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:351,449
The gang in the tower, they had their little kingdom, and they weren’t giving it up for anyone.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[580]:449,567
That was one of the few times we went full convent; SAWs, nades, that’s when the Bradleys started making a comeback.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[581]:0,78
After Chicago, the brass knew we were now in a full, multithreat environment.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[581]:78,137
It was back to hard covers and body armor, even in summer.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[581]:137,157
Thanks, Windy City.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[581]:157,219
Each squad was issued pamphlets with the “Threat Pyramid.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[582]:0,55
It was ranked according to probability, not lethality.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[582]:55,131
Zack at the bottom, then F-critters, ferals, quislings, and finally LaMOEs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[582]:131,298
I know a lot of guys from AG South like to bitch about how they always had it tougher on their end, ’cause, for us, winter took care of Zack’s whole threat level.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[582]:298,351
Yeah, sure, and replaced it with another one: winter!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:0,90
What do they say the average temperature’s dropped, ten degrees, fifteen in some areas?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:90,259
6 Yeah, we had it real easy, up to our ass in gray snow, knowing that for every five Zacksicles you cracked there’d be at least as many up and at ’em at first thaw.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:259,340
At least the guys down south knew that once they swept an area, it stayed swept.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:340,401
They didn’t have to worry about rear area attacks like us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:401,443
We swept every area at least three times.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:443,517
We used everything from ramrods and sniffer Ks to high-tech ground radar.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:517,577
Over and over again, and all of this in the dead of winter.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:577,631
We lost more guys to frostbite than to anything else.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[583]:631,891
And still, every spring, you knew, you just knew…it’d be like, “oh shit, here we go again.” I mean, even today, with all the sweeps and civilian volunteer groups, spring’s like winter used to be, nature letting us know the good life’s over for now.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[584]
Tell me about liberating the isolated zones.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:0,39
Always a hard fight, every single one.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:39,116
Remember these zones were still under siege, hundreds, maybe even thousands.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:116,284
The people holed up in the twin forts of Comerica Park/Ford Field, they must have had a combined moat—that’s what we called them, moats—of at least a million Gs.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:284,353
That was a three-day slugfest, made Hope look like a minor skirmish.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:353,424
That was the only time I ever really thought we were gonna be overrun.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:424,512
They piled up so high I thought we’d be buried, literally, in a landslide of corpses.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:512,588
Battles like that, they’d leave you so fried, just wasted, body and mind.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:588,656
You’d want to sleep, nothing more, not eat or bathe or even fuck.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[585]:656,741
You’d just want to find someplace warm and dry, close your eyes, forget everything.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[586]
What were the reactions of the people who you liberated?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[587]:0,15
Kind of a mix.
====
