It was like what you’d think war was supposed to be, those old black-and-whites of GIs marching into Paris or wherever.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[590]:204,224
We were rock stars.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[590]:224,351
I got more…well…if there’s a bunch of little dudes between here and the Hero City that happen to look like me…[Laughs.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[591]
But there were exceptions.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[592]:0,15
Yeah, I guess.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[592]:15,124
Maybe not all the time but there’d be this one person, this angry face in the crowd screaming shit at you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[592]:124,354
“What the fuck took you so long?” “My husband died two weeks ago!” “My mother died waiting for you!” “We lost half our people last summer!” “Where were you when we needed you?” People holding up photos, faces.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[592]:354,469
When we marched into Janesville, Wisconsin, someone was holding up a sign with a picture of a smiling little girl.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[592]:469,592
The words above it read “Better late than never?” He got beat down by his own people; they shouldn’t have done that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[592]:592,692
That’s the kind of shit we saw, shit that keeps you awake when you haven’t slept in five nights.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[593]:0,87
Rarely, like, blue-moon rarely, we’d enter a zone where we were totally not welcome.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[593]:87,152
In Valley City, North Dakota, they were like, “Fuck you, army!
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[593]:152,194
