Yeah, and I read a lot about the trials.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[602]
How did they make you feel?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[603]:0,22
Shit, I don’t know.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[603]:22,54
Who am I to judge those people?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[603]:54,107
I wasn’t there, I didn’t have to deal with that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[603]:107,218
This conversation we’re having now, this question of “what if,” I didn’t have time for that back then.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[603]:218,242
I still had a job to do.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[604]:0,50
I know historians like to talk about how the U.S.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[604]:50,104
Army had such a low casualty rate during the advance.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[604]:104,173
Low, as in compared to other countries, China or maybe the Russkies.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[604]:173,229
Low, as in only counting the casualties caused by Zack.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[604]:229,324
There were a million ways to get it on that road and over two-thirds weren’t on that pyramid.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[605]:0,114
Sickness was a big one, the kinds of diseases that were supposed to be gone, like, in the Dark Ages or something.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[605]:114,296
Yeah, we took our pills, had our shots, ate well, and had regular checkups, but there was just so much shit everywhere, in the dirt, the water, in the rain, and the air we breathed.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[605]:296,420
Every time we entered a city, or liberated a zone, at least one guy would be gone, if not dead then removed for quarantine.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[605]:420,472
In Detroit, we lost a whole platoon to Spanish flu.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[605]:472,556
The brass really freaked on that one, quarantined the whole battalion for two weeks.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:0,88
Then there were mines and booby traps, some civilian, some laid during our bugout west.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:88,119
Made a lot of sense back then.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:119,183
Just seed mile after mile and wait for Zack to blow himself up.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:183,229
Only problem is, mines don’t work that way.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:229,315
They don’t blow up a human body, they take off a leg or ankle or the family jewels.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:315,616
That’s what they’re designed for, not to kill people, but to wound ’em so the army will spend valuable resources keeping them alive, and then send ’em home in a wheelchair so Ma and Pa Civilian can be reminded every time they see ’em that maybe supporting this war isn’t such a good idea.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:616,661
But Zack has no home, no Ma and Pa Civilian.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:661,911
All conventional mines do is create a bunch of crippled ghouls that, if anything, just makes your job that much harder because you want them upright and easy to spot, not crawling around the weeds waiting to be stepped on like land mines themselves.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:911,1114
You couldn’t know where most mines were; a lot of the units that set them during the retreat hadn’t marked them correctly or had lost their coordinates or simply weren’t alive anymore to tell you.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[606]:1114,1217
And then you had all those stupid fuckin’ LaMOE jobs, the punji stakes and trip-wired shotgun shells.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:0,71
I lost a buddy of mine that way, in a Wal-Mart in Rochester, New York.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:71,119
He was born in El Salvador but grew up in Cali.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:119,161
You ever heard of the Boyle Heights Boyz?
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:161,275
They were these hard-core LA bangers who were deported back to El Salvador because they were technically illegal.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:275,324
My buddy was plopped there right before the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:324,446
He fought his way back up through Mexico, all during the worst days of the Panic, all on foot with nothing but a machete.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:446,515
He didn’t have any family left, no friends, just his adopted home.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:515,546
He loved this country so much.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:546,610
Reminded me of my grandpa, you know, the whole immigrant thing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:610,720
And then to catch a twelve-gauge in the face, probably set by a LaMOE who’d stopped breathing years before.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[607]:720,752
Fuckin’ mines and booby traps.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:0,33
And then you just had accidents.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:33,88
So many buildings had been weakened from the fighting.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:88,144
Throw in years of neglect, and foot after foot of snow.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:144,216
Whole roofs collapsed, no warning, whole structures just tumbling down.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:216,247
I lost someone else like that.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:247,322
She had a contact, a feral running at her across an abandoned auto garage.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:322,366
She fired her weapon, that’s all it took.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:366,437
I don’t know how many pounds of snow and ice brought that roof down.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:437,474
She was…we were…close, you know.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:474,506
We never did anything about it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[608]:506,643
I guess we thought that would make it “official.” I guess we thought it would make it easier in case something happened to one of us.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[609]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[610]
[He looks over at the bleachers, smiling at his wife.]
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[611]
 
