/html/body/div/div[15]/p[615]
 
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:0,38
And then there were psych casualties.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:38,72
More than anything else combined.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:72,160
Sometimes we’d march into barricaded zones and find nothing but rat-gnawed skeletons.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:160,314
I’m talking about the zones that weren’t overrun, the ones that fell to starvation or disease, or just a feeling that tomorrow wasn’t worth seeing.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:314,409
We once broke into a church in Kansas where it was clear the adults killed all the kids first.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:409,688
One guy in our platoon, an Amish guy, used to read all their suicide notes, commit them to memory, then give himself this little cut, this tiny half-inch nick somewhere on his body so he would “never forget.” Crazy bastard was sliced from his neck to the bottom of his toes.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[616]:688,762
When the LT found out about it…sectioned eight his ass right outa there.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[617]:0,47
Most of the Eight Balls were later in the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[617]:47,117
Not from the stress, though, you understand, but from the lack of it.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[617]:117,318
We all knew it would be over soon, and I think a lot of people who’d been holding it together for so long must’ve had that little voice that said, “Hey, buddy, it’s cool now, you can let go.”
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[618]:0,97
I knew this one guy, massive ’roidasaurus, he’d been a professional wrestler before the war.
====
/html/body/div/div[15]/p[618]:97,211
We were walking up the freeway near Pulaski, New York, when the wind picked up the scent of a jackknifed big rig.
